00:00:21.930 --> 00:00:27.070
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: OK, so
today I would like to cover--

00:00:27.070 --> 00:00:29.070
to start, well, I will
do a lot of things today.

00:00:29.070 --> 00:00:33.860
But to begin with, I would
like to solve two applications

00:00:33.860 --> 00:00:35.960
of Fermat's principle.

00:00:35.960 --> 00:00:39.800
And the simplest possible thing
that we try to do in optics,

00:00:39.800 --> 00:00:42.030
and that is to focus.

00:00:42.030 --> 00:00:44.670
So the one focus will
come up again and again.

00:00:44.670 --> 00:00:46.440
It basically refers
to the idea--

00:00:46.440 --> 00:00:48.570
hi, Colin.

00:00:48.570 --> 00:00:54.150
It refers to the idea that we
have rays, a bundle of rays

00:00:54.150 --> 00:00:56.610
that are propagating.

00:00:56.610 --> 00:00:59.840
And focusing means that we try
to force these rays to meet

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:01.342
at one point.

00:01:01.342 --> 00:01:03.300
So this, of course, is
very useful for imaging,

00:01:03.300 --> 00:01:06.570
but even simpler, if
you want to collect

00:01:06.570 --> 00:01:09.570
all of the light
energy, for example,

00:01:09.570 --> 00:01:12.450
for a solar concentrator,
or a satellite dish,

00:01:12.450 --> 00:01:14.998
or something like that.

00:01:14.998 --> 00:01:16.790
Then basically, this
is what you try to do.

00:01:16.790 --> 00:01:19.900
You try to get the rays that
are coming from the source,

00:01:19.900 --> 00:01:21.880
and focus them into a point.

00:01:21.880 --> 00:01:24.970
And this is valid, of
course, in the entire regime

00:01:24.970 --> 00:01:27.390
of electromagnetic waves--

00:01:27.390 --> 00:01:33.040
whether microwaves, or visible
light, or even higher--

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:38.020
provided that the element
that we use to focus the rays

00:01:38.020 --> 00:01:40.210
is much bigger than
the wavelength.

00:01:40.210 --> 00:01:42.850
And here, I'm leaving
it deliberately vague

00:01:42.850 --> 00:01:44.200
how much bigger.

00:01:44.200 --> 00:01:50.900
But think about it that is maybe
a few thousand of wavelengths,

00:01:50.900 --> 00:01:52.690
or few hundred of wavelengths.

00:01:52.690 --> 00:01:55.610
In the microwave case,
that's not exactly true.

00:01:55.610 --> 00:01:58.270
The RF wavelength maybe
a couple of centimeters.

00:01:58.270 --> 00:02:01.330
The typical satellite
dish is about the meter,

00:02:01.330 --> 00:02:03.790
so we're talking about
50 to 100 wavelength.

00:02:03.790 --> 00:02:07.480
But anyway, still the
approximations are valid.

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:11.140
So the simplest way to
do this kind of operation

00:02:11.140 --> 00:02:15.700
to focus the light into a
point so it can be detected

00:02:15.700 --> 00:02:22.210
is with a reflector, a mirror
whose surface is curved.

00:02:22.210 --> 00:02:24.940
And you know from experience
if you look at the spoon

00:02:24.940 --> 00:02:28.240
that, well, funny things happen
if you look at the spoon.

00:02:28.240 --> 00:02:33.850
We will talk about that
perhaps a little bit later.

00:02:33.850 --> 00:02:36.085
But you know that the
spoon forms images,

00:02:36.085 --> 00:02:41.380
so this is basically a
simplification or idealization

00:02:41.380 --> 00:02:43.010
of a spoon.

00:02:43.010 --> 00:02:45.880
So let's say that we
have this surface.

00:02:45.880 --> 00:02:50.170
And for now, even though the
label says parabolic reflector,

00:02:50.170 --> 00:02:53.180
I will pretend that I don't
know the shape of the surface.

00:02:53.180 --> 00:02:56.740
So s of x is an unknown
to be determined.

00:02:56.740 --> 00:03:00.530
And the goal, of
course, is to have

00:03:00.530 --> 00:03:07.030
rays that are coming as parallel
rays onto the parabol line,

00:03:07.030 --> 00:03:08.710
onto this unknown shape.

00:03:08.710 --> 00:03:11.320
And our goal is to
focus these rays

00:03:11.320 --> 00:03:16.190
into a point on the
axis of the surface.

00:03:16.190 --> 00:03:17.750
And what you see.

00:03:17.750 --> 00:03:24.047
You see here that I put
the symbol of infinity.

00:03:24.047 --> 00:03:25.880
I will mention that
also a little bit later.

00:03:25.880 --> 00:03:31.220
If we have rays that are
parallel, you can think--

00:03:31.220 --> 00:03:34.820
according to Euclidean geometry,
parallel rays never meet.

00:03:34.820 --> 00:03:37.820
Or another way to say it is
that parallel rays, if they ever

00:03:37.820 --> 00:03:40.760
meet, that would be at infinity,
at a very, very long distance

00:03:40.760 --> 00:03:41.490
away.

00:03:41.490 --> 00:03:43.640
So when the object
of the imaging system

00:03:43.640 --> 00:03:48.320
is very far away, such
as the sun, or a star,

00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:51.140
or a really remote source.

00:03:51.140 --> 00:03:53.540
Then we can say that
the ray is coming

00:03:53.540 --> 00:03:55.250
from that object
that are parallel,

00:03:55.250 --> 00:03:58.020
or that are coming
from infinity.

00:03:58.020 --> 00:04:00.070
So the objective here
is, again, to determine

00:04:00.070 --> 00:04:02.940
the shape of the
surface, s of x, such

00:04:02.940 --> 00:04:07.003
that the rays all
focus at a point, f.

00:04:07.003 --> 00:04:08.670
So there's a number
of ways of doing it.

00:04:08.670 --> 00:04:12.490
One is for example, I can apply
the law of reflection anywhere

00:04:12.490 --> 00:04:13.120
in the surface.

00:04:13.120 --> 00:04:14.920
I have the array appearing here.

00:04:14.920 --> 00:04:17.500
I can compute the
normal to the ray--

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:19.089
I'm sorry, the
normal to the surface

00:04:19.089 --> 00:04:20.980
at that point of
existence of the ray.

00:04:20.980 --> 00:04:22.600
And I can apply the
law of reflection.

00:04:22.600 --> 00:04:24.383
I can solve the
problem this way.

00:04:24.383 --> 00:04:26.800
But that is actually a very
complicated way of solving it.

00:04:29.340 --> 00:04:30.780
Much work.

00:04:30.780 --> 00:04:32.500
So being, I guess, lazy.

00:04:35.010 --> 00:04:36.630
The best way to
solve this problem

00:04:36.630 --> 00:04:39.000
is to invoke the
Fermat's principle.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:41.790
And Fermat's principle
says, again, to remind you,

00:04:41.790 --> 00:04:47.490
says that rays that
depart from a common point

00:04:47.490 --> 00:04:50.130
and arrive at another point.

00:04:50.130 --> 00:04:54.550
They have to follow the
minimum optical path.

00:04:54.550 --> 00:04:57.360
A corollary to
that is that if you

00:04:57.360 --> 00:04:59.940
have two rays that
start at the same point

00:04:59.940 --> 00:05:02.130
and meet again at
the same point,

00:05:02.130 --> 00:05:04.800
then these rays must
follow the same path.

00:05:04.800 --> 00:05:08.130
Because if one of those
rays follows a shorter path,

00:05:08.130 --> 00:05:10.800
it means that the other ray
that followed the longer path

00:05:10.800 --> 00:05:12.760
is violating Fermat's principle.

00:05:12.760 --> 00:05:14.590
And that cannot happen.

00:05:14.590 --> 00:05:17.280
So the way we're
thinking about this here

00:05:17.280 --> 00:05:19.560
is to take, for
example, the center

00:05:19.560 --> 00:05:25.170
ray that is going directly on
axis, that started at infinity.

00:05:25.170 --> 00:05:26.340
We go to the reflector.

00:05:26.340 --> 00:05:28.440
It will be reflected
exactly backwards,

00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:31.070
and will go through
the focal point, f.

00:05:31.070 --> 00:05:33.840
If we take another
ray that is away

00:05:33.840 --> 00:05:38.350
from the central axis
of the unknown surface.

00:05:38.350 --> 00:05:40.800
Then this ray also
started at infinity.

00:05:40.800 --> 00:05:44.340
It gets reflected, and then,
again, meets at that point, f.

00:05:44.340 --> 00:05:47.990
So therefore, the pattern
that these two rays followed

00:05:47.990 --> 00:05:51.020
must be the same.

00:05:51.020 --> 00:05:53.130
So how do we compute this path?

00:05:53.130 --> 00:05:56.290
Well, if you look
at the central ray.

00:06:01.960 --> 00:06:04.300
The central ray is
coming from infinity.

00:06:04.300 --> 00:06:07.650
I will use the plane passing
through the focal point

00:06:07.650 --> 00:06:09.340
as my reference.

00:06:09.340 --> 00:06:13.660
And I will calculate
the path back and forth

00:06:13.660 --> 00:06:16.180
from the focal point to
the reflector and back.

00:06:16.180 --> 00:06:18.310
So I basically
calculate this path.

00:06:18.310 --> 00:06:21.610
This path obviously
equals 2 times f.

00:06:21.610 --> 00:06:26.680
By f, I denote the focal
distance of the reflector.

00:06:26.680 --> 00:06:30.730
That is the distance at which
the rays come to a focus.

00:06:30.730 --> 00:06:32.500
And the other path
I will compute

00:06:32.500 --> 00:06:38.140
is I will ignore the path of the
ray up to the reference plane.

00:06:38.140 --> 00:06:42.600
And then I will compute
this path over here.

00:06:42.600 --> 00:06:44.030
So how do you compute this path?

00:06:44.030 --> 00:06:49.390
Well, the shape of the
paraboloid is s of x.

00:06:49.390 --> 00:06:54.560
So basically, s of x is the
elevation of the unknown shape

00:06:54.560 --> 00:06:57.920
with respect to the
other reference plane

00:06:57.920 --> 00:07:01.700
that passes through the
bottom of the unknown shape.

00:07:01.700 --> 00:07:05.990
So therefore, this
distance here is f minus s,

00:07:05.990 --> 00:07:10.960
because it equals the focal
distance minus the elevation

00:07:10.960 --> 00:07:13.580
of the reflector.

00:07:13.580 --> 00:07:19.220
And the other-- this
distance over here.

00:07:19.220 --> 00:07:20.720
OK, so let me write it down.

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:23.510
So it is f minus s.

00:07:23.510 --> 00:07:28.790
This is the first
segment of the ray part.

00:07:28.790 --> 00:07:32.600
And the other is the hypotenuse
of this orthogonal triangle,

00:07:32.600 --> 00:07:40.400
where one side of the
triangle equals x.

00:07:40.400 --> 00:07:43.930
The other side of the
triangle equals f plus s.

00:07:43.930 --> 00:07:46.820
And all I have to do is I have
to apply Pythagoras' theorem.

00:07:50.450 --> 00:07:56.690
OK, so this is the path of
the ray that arrived away

00:07:56.690 --> 00:07:58.340
from the optical axis.

00:07:58.340 --> 00:08:00.410
And, of course, this
must equal the path

00:08:00.410 --> 00:08:05.940
of the ray that is exactly on
the axis that equals to 2f.

00:08:05.940 --> 00:08:09.940
So now, we can play with
his formula a little bit.

00:08:09.940 --> 00:08:11.860
I skip the derivation
in the notes.

00:08:11.860 --> 00:08:14.790
Actually, I didn't quite skip
the derivation of the notes.

00:08:14.790 --> 00:08:20.740
So instead of deriving it
here, I will just animate it.

00:08:20.740 --> 00:08:23.350
And if we do the
algebra here, we

00:08:23.350 --> 00:08:26.890
can basically eliminate
one of the focal distances,

00:08:26.890 --> 00:08:28.780
bring that to the other side.

00:08:28.780 --> 00:08:31.780
And then do a little bit
more algebraic manipulation.

00:08:31.780 --> 00:08:35.679
And after not too much work, we
have this expression over here

00:08:35.679 --> 00:08:38.500
for the elevation of
the unknown shape.

00:08:38.500 --> 00:08:41.232
And clearly, what you see
over that is a parabola.

00:08:41.232 --> 00:08:42.940
Of course, it turned
out to be a parabola

00:08:42.940 --> 00:08:46.450
because I did the calculation
in the cross section--

00:08:46.450 --> 00:08:49.600
in one cross section
of the optical element.

00:08:49.600 --> 00:08:51.400
In reality, all
of these elements

00:08:51.400 --> 00:08:56.700
are rotationally symmetric
surfaces of revolution.

00:08:56.700 --> 00:08:59.560
So the reason I
call it a paraboloid

00:08:59.560 --> 00:09:02.620
and not a parabola is
because I take this shape,

00:09:02.620 --> 00:09:05.050
and then I spin it
around the optical axis

00:09:05.050 --> 00:09:07.120
in order to get
the familiar ball

00:09:07.120 --> 00:09:09.070
shape of the paraboloid this.

00:09:09.070 --> 00:09:13.570
But to do a little
less math here,

00:09:13.570 --> 00:09:16.330
and to keep my life simple, I
will only do these calculations

00:09:16.330 --> 00:09:18.380
in one plane.

00:09:18.380 --> 00:09:21.440
So turns out to be
a simple parabola.

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:25.040
So then this is
your final answer.

00:09:25.040 --> 00:09:28.490
This is the shape
of a reflector that

00:09:28.490 --> 00:09:31.630
will take a set
of parallel rays,

00:09:31.630 --> 00:09:35.660
and focus them into a
focal point in front

00:09:35.660 --> 00:09:38.670
of the reflector.

00:09:38.670 --> 00:09:39.720
So these are very nice.

00:09:39.720 --> 00:09:43.560
And we actually got our
first imaging system.

00:09:43.560 --> 00:09:46.110
We managed to compute
its focal length

00:09:46.110 --> 00:09:49.820
as a function of the
shape of the element.

00:09:49.820 --> 00:09:52.070
There's a few things that I
would like to remark here.

00:09:52.070 --> 00:09:55.420
One is, for example, that
this works very nicely when

00:09:55.420 --> 00:10:00.430
the rays are indeed incident
parallel to the normal

00:10:00.430 --> 00:10:02.720
at the center of
the parabola here.

00:10:02.720 --> 00:10:06.530
If you imagine that I take
this set of rays and I tilt it.

00:10:06.530 --> 00:10:09.160
Then a little bit of thought
will convince yourself

00:10:09.160 --> 00:10:11.620
that it doesn't work
so nicely anymore.

00:10:11.620 --> 00:10:15.030
If you were to then
come in parallel rays,

00:10:15.030 --> 00:10:19.150
then the rays will
kind of focus,

00:10:19.150 --> 00:10:24.020
but they would fail to meet all
at once at the focal point, f.

00:10:24.020 --> 00:10:26.020
So this is a perfect
focusing element

00:10:26.020 --> 00:10:29.200
for on axis incident rays.

00:10:29.200 --> 00:10:30.880
But it would be not
so perfect anymore

00:10:30.880 --> 00:10:34.690
if the rays are
arriving off axis.

00:10:34.690 --> 00:10:36.320
That's one observation
to keep in mind.

00:10:36.320 --> 00:10:39.990
This will come up again later.

00:10:39.990 --> 00:10:41.740
One thing I would like
to say is that this

00:10:41.740 --> 00:10:43.930
is a very nice element, indeed.

00:10:43.930 --> 00:10:45.910
But in some cases,
it is not practical

00:10:45.910 --> 00:10:49.510
because as you can see,
the focus is actually

00:10:49.510 --> 00:10:50.600
in front of the element.

00:10:50.600 --> 00:10:52.630
So if you were to
detect the light,

00:10:52.630 --> 00:10:56.230
you would have to put,
for example, a photo diode

00:10:56.230 --> 00:10:59.500
or some transducer at
this location, which

00:10:59.500 --> 00:11:03.263
means you are actually
blocking the path of the light.

00:11:03.263 --> 00:11:04.680
AUDIENCE: I have
a quick question.

00:11:10.435 --> 00:11:12.560
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: I'm
sorry, I can not hear you.

00:11:12.560 --> 00:11:14.960
AUDIENCE: I can understand
how the rays have

00:11:14.960 --> 00:11:16.910
a minimal optical path.

00:11:16.910 --> 00:11:18.410
But I don't understand
why they have

00:11:18.410 --> 00:11:20.390
to have the same optical path.

00:11:20.390 --> 00:11:23.990
For example, you let
it equal to 2f, which

00:11:23.990 --> 00:11:26.150
was at the center distance.

00:11:26.150 --> 00:11:28.910
So isn't it possible that the
minimum optical path does not

00:11:28.910 --> 00:11:29.810
equal 2f?

00:11:29.810 --> 00:11:31.240
Or why is that the case?

00:11:33.292 --> 00:11:34.750
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Take two rays.

00:11:34.750 --> 00:11:38.650
In our case, one ray [INAUDIBLE]
from infinity, and they both

00:11:38.650 --> 00:11:43.280
meet at F. So the rays can
take different optical paths.

00:11:43.280 --> 00:11:45.650
One can go like this, the
other can go like this.

00:11:45.650 --> 00:11:47.930
And doing our rays in general.

00:11:47.930 --> 00:11:53.050
So imagine that this has path
l1, and this has path l2.

00:11:53.050 --> 00:11:54.980
And imagine, for the
sake of argument,

00:11:54.980 --> 00:11:58.450
that l1 is less than l2.

00:11:58.450 --> 00:12:06.700
Fermat's principle says
that if the ray, number one,

00:12:06.700 --> 00:12:10.240
goes through the first
point from the origin

00:12:10.240 --> 00:12:11.890
to the destination.

00:12:11.890 --> 00:12:13.570
It follows a certain path.

00:12:13.570 --> 00:12:15.700
This path has to be minimal.

00:12:15.700 --> 00:12:17.780
But now, look at ray number two.

00:12:17.780 --> 00:12:22.090
This ray also goes from the same
origin to the same destination,

00:12:22.090 --> 00:12:25.000
but follows a
longer optical path.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:29.240
Therefore, the second ray has
to violate Fermat's principle.

00:12:29.240 --> 00:12:32.657
So this is what we call
mathematics abduction to--

00:12:32.657 --> 00:12:33.490
what do you call it?

00:12:33.490 --> 00:12:35.020
To absurdum.

00:12:35.020 --> 00:12:36.880
That's right,
abduction to absurdum.

00:12:36.880 --> 00:12:39.580
In other words, by
assuming that the rays have

00:12:39.580 --> 00:12:43.060
unequal optical
paths, we arrived

00:12:43.060 --> 00:12:46.170
at a conclusion that is
inconsistent with Fermat's

00:12:46.170 --> 00:12:46.990
principle.

00:12:46.990 --> 00:12:49.990
So therefore, this
has to be discarded.

00:12:49.990 --> 00:12:53.110
The only possibility
is that l1 equals l2.

00:12:53.110 --> 00:12:56.080
So because the two rays
start at the same origin

00:12:56.080 --> 00:12:58.000
and arrive at the
same destination,

00:12:58.000 --> 00:12:59.850
they must have the
same optical path.

00:13:02.680 --> 00:13:03.673
Did that make sense?

00:13:06.982 --> 00:13:09.190
AUDIENCE: For example, in
the homework problem, where

00:13:09.190 --> 00:13:15.193
you have the swimmer and the
lifeguard, well, I guess--

00:13:15.193 --> 00:13:16.610
I'll think about
it a little more.

00:13:16.610 --> 00:13:16.820
Yeah, makes sense.

00:13:16.820 --> 00:13:17.320
Thanks.

00:13:24.060 --> 00:13:25.060
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: OK.

00:13:27.730 --> 00:13:31.840
So for the cases where the
paraboloid is not convenient.

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:33.580
Actually, I should
say for the cases

00:13:33.580 --> 00:13:36.850
where the reflector
is not convenient,

00:13:36.850 --> 00:13:39.520
because of the problem
of blocking the ray

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:42.760
path at the focal point.

00:13:42.760 --> 00:13:44.920
It is perhaps more
convenient to attempt

00:13:44.920 --> 00:13:48.700
to use a refractive optical
element that is a dielectric.

00:13:48.700 --> 00:13:53.510
And try to focus the rays using
now, again, a curved surface.

00:13:53.510 --> 00:13:57.900
But in this case, it is a curved
surface refractive index n.

00:13:57.900 --> 00:13:59.440
And for simplicity,
I will assume

00:13:59.440 --> 00:14:02.380
that the rays are, again,
are coming from free space,

00:14:02.380 --> 00:14:04.790
from vacuum, or from air.

00:14:04.790 --> 00:14:06.640
So the index of
refraction is actually

00:14:06.640 --> 00:14:09.090
one on the left
hand side over here.

00:14:09.090 --> 00:14:11.910
On the right hand side, it is n.

00:14:11.910 --> 00:14:15.450
So in this case, again,
I have the same problem.

00:14:15.450 --> 00:14:20.390
I have an unknown shape, s
of x, that I should follow,

00:14:20.390 --> 00:14:25.050
that I must somehow
shape my refractor.

00:14:25.050 --> 00:14:27.090
And one could assume
that this is anything.

00:14:27.090 --> 00:14:28.480
It could be, again, a parabola.

00:14:28.480 --> 00:14:30.872
It could be a circle,
I mean, a sphere.

00:14:30.872 --> 00:14:32.580
It could be a number
of different things.

00:14:32.580 --> 00:14:36.010
The question, what is it really.

00:14:36.010 --> 00:14:38.190
So the question is actually
the same as the question

00:14:38.190 --> 00:14:40.700
that I asked before.

00:14:40.700 --> 00:14:44.900
And to answer it, we will
actually follow once again

00:14:44.900 --> 00:14:46.480
the same argument.

00:14:46.480 --> 00:14:50.630
We will use Fermat to argue
that since the two rays started

00:14:50.630 --> 00:14:52.860
at the same point, infinity.

00:14:52.860 --> 00:14:56.510
And they meet at the same
point, F, at the same target,

00:14:56.510 --> 00:14:59.970
F. They must follow
the same optical path.

00:14:59.970 --> 00:15:04.130
So in this case, I will apply
Fermat with the reference plane

00:15:04.130 --> 00:15:10.850
that is tangential at the
apex of the known refractive--

00:15:10.850 --> 00:15:14.600
I'm sorry, of the
unknown refractor shape.

00:15:14.600 --> 00:15:18.080
And I will compute the
path of the own axis

00:15:18.080 --> 00:15:20.550
ray, which is very easy.

00:15:20.550 --> 00:15:23.610
So this path, you have to
be a little bit careful now

00:15:23.610 --> 00:15:26.300
when we define the optical path.

00:15:26.300 --> 00:15:30.710
If you remember, the
optical path in general.

00:15:30.710 --> 00:15:33.830
Optical path length
equals the integral

00:15:33.830 --> 00:15:43.390
along the ray trajectory of the
index of refraction times dl.

00:15:43.390 --> 00:15:45.790
So what this means
now in our case

00:15:45.790 --> 00:15:49.510
is that the optical path
length for this segment

00:15:49.510 --> 00:15:53.680
of the rays between the
apex and the focal point

00:15:53.680 --> 00:16:01.600
equals f, the distance, times
the index of refraction,

00:16:01.600 --> 00:16:05.310
in order to convert it
to proper optical path.

00:16:05.310 --> 00:16:06.157
OK, so that's easy.

00:16:06.157 --> 00:16:07.740
Now, we have to
compute the other one.

00:16:11.953 --> 00:16:14.120
So here's, again, I will
exaggerate it a little bit.

00:16:14.120 --> 00:16:22.160
Here is, again, my
unknown shape, s of x.

00:16:22.160 --> 00:16:29.810
And here is the ray that is
arriving at some distance, x,

00:16:29.810 --> 00:16:32.270
from the apex.

00:16:32.270 --> 00:16:36.260
And this ray, according
to my postulate here,

00:16:36.260 --> 00:16:41.990
will meet the axis
at distance small f.

00:16:41.990 --> 00:16:46.862
To reach the point, uppercase
f, that is the focal point.

00:16:46.862 --> 00:16:49.070
So again, I have to do a
little bit of geometry here.

00:16:49.070 --> 00:16:51.980
This distance is s of x.

00:16:51.980 --> 00:16:55.610
Because this distance, again, is
the elevation of the refractor

00:16:55.610 --> 00:16:58.920
shape relative to my
reference plane over here.

00:17:04.170 --> 00:17:09.750
So this equals s plus this
distance, which again, is

00:17:09.750 --> 00:17:11.984
the hypotenuse of a triangle.

00:17:11.984 --> 00:17:13.859
But I have to be, again,
a little bit careful

00:17:13.859 --> 00:17:17.930
because this segment
over here now,

00:17:17.930 --> 00:17:20.270
again, is inside the refractor.

00:17:20.270 --> 00:17:21.890
So before I do
anything else, again, I

00:17:21.890 --> 00:17:24.390
have to multiply by the
index of refraction.

00:17:24.390 --> 00:17:26.930
So it has to be n, the
index of refraction,

00:17:26.930 --> 00:17:31.910
times the hypotenuse
length, which

00:17:31.910 --> 00:17:34.353
equals the square
root of the two sides,

00:17:34.353 --> 00:17:35.395
of the two sides squared.

00:17:42.743 --> 00:17:43.410
What am I doing?

00:17:43.410 --> 00:17:44.780
I'm sorry.

00:17:44.780 --> 00:17:48.840
x squared plus f
minus s squared.

00:17:48.840 --> 00:17:50.304
That's the correct expression.

00:17:57.890 --> 00:17:59.840
OK, and [INAUDIBLE] in
fact I could see it,

00:17:59.840 --> 00:18:01.423
because my computer
has a preview.

00:18:01.423 --> 00:18:02.840
So I can see the
equation, but I'm

00:18:02.840 --> 00:18:06.290
trying not to see it when
I'm deriving things here.

00:18:06.290 --> 00:18:08.170
OK, so that is the
equation, then.

00:18:08.170 --> 00:18:09.670
So again, according
to the argument.

00:18:09.670 --> 00:18:11.795
Actually, let me repeat it
once again, because this

00:18:11.795 --> 00:18:13.740
is a-- it's a very basic point.

00:18:13.740 --> 00:18:15.020
We have two rays here.

00:18:15.020 --> 00:18:17.220
One is going on axis.

00:18:17.220 --> 00:18:20.650
There is no refraction here,
because it is incident exactly

00:18:20.650 --> 00:18:23.250
normally on the surface.

00:18:23.250 --> 00:18:25.390
And then it propagates
at distance, f.

00:18:25.390 --> 00:18:29.720
So the optical path length
of this ray equals n times f.

00:18:29.720 --> 00:18:32.560
Then I have another ray that
propagated a little bit further

00:18:32.560 --> 00:18:36.840
in there because it arrives
at the elevated portion

00:18:36.840 --> 00:18:39.220
of the refractor.

00:18:39.220 --> 00:18:42.410
And then it bends in some
way that we don't know yet.

00:18:42.410 --> 00:18:44.680
But what we do know
is that we want,

00:18:44.680 --> 00:18:47.310
we demand, we
require, so to speak,

00:18:47.310 --> 00:18:50.050
this ray to go through
the same point, F.

00:18:50.050 --> 00:18:53.150
So the fact that the ray goes
through the same point, F.

00:18:53.150 --> 00:18:58.090
It means that it must follow the
same path as the one axis ray.

00:18:58.090 --> 00:19:02.320
If this ray, for example,
had followed a shorter path.

00:19:02.320 --> 00:19:04.620
Then there's no reason for
this ray to go this way.

00:19:04.620 --> 00:19:06.670
It should have gone
this way as well,

00:19:06.670 --> 00:19:09.280
because if it
hadn't, it would be

00:19:09.280 --> 00:19:11.860
violating Fermat's principle.

00:19:11.860 --> 00:19:13.130
That is the argument.

00:19:13.130 --> 00:19:14.830
So therefore, there
are two paths.

00:19:14.830 --> 00:19:17.530
This path, and this path.

00:19:17.530 --> 00:19:19.240
They must be exactly equal.

00:19:19.240 --> 00:19:22.930
So this is what this
equation says over that.

00:19:22.930 --> 00:19:25.910
OK, this equation now.

00:19:25.910 --> 00:19:30.504
Does anybody know what
this equation represents?

00:19:33.203 --> 00:19:35.120
If you have looked at
the notes ahead of time,

00:19:35.120 --> 00:19:36.443
you know the answer.

00:19:36.443 --> 00:19:38.360
If you ever looked at
the notes, this equation

00:19:38.360 --> 00:19:40.040
doesn't mean much.

00:19:40.040 --> 00:19:42.020
However, it can be manipulated.

00:19:42.020 --> 00:19:44.670
And I did not do all the
algebra in the notes.

00:19:44.670 --> 00:19:47.790
I skipped a few steps.

00:19:47.790 --> 00:19:50.090
So the first thing you
do is you basically try

00:19:50.090 --> 00:19:52.010
to get rid of the square root.

00:19:52.010 --> 00:19:55.140
So you bring this
s on that side.

00:19:55.140 --> 00:19:56.780
You take squares of both sides.

00:19:56.780 --> 00:19:59.300
You do a little bit of algebra.

00:19:59.300 --> 00:20:01.530
You bring it to this form.

00:20:01.530 --> 00:20:04.170
Then this-- it still
doesn't look very nice.

00:20:04.170 --> 00:20:06.870
So what you do is you try
to write it to complete

00:20:06.870 --> 00:20:09.070
the sum of squares here.

00:20:09.070 --> 00:20:12.570
So that's a little bit messy.

00:20:12.570 --> 00:20:15.210
I will let you do it by
yourselves, if you're

00:20:15.210 --> 00:20:16.217
interested and curious.

00:20:16.217 --> 00:20:18.300
If you get stuck, and you
don't know how to do it,

00:20:18.300 --> 00:20:21.600
I will post the complete
derivation on the website.

00:20:21.600 --> 00:20:24.030
But anyway, after a
little bit more algebra,

00:20:24.030 --> 00:20:26.470
you get a result
that looks like this.

00:20:26.470 --> 00:20:30.480
It looks like a square
of the surface shape, s,

00:20:30.480 --> 00:20:33.570
minus the displacement,
times another square

00:20:33.570 --> 00:20:37.210
of the coordinate x
equals a constant.

00:20:37.210 --> 00:20:40.230
And this type of
equation in general,

00:20:40.230 --> 00:20:44.860
an equation of the form
s square over constant,

00:20:44.860 --> 00:20:50.610
plus x square over constant
equals another constant, which

00:20:50.610 --> 00:20:52.290
might as well be one.

00:20:52.290 --> 00:20:55.650
This equation
represents an ellipse.

00:20:55.650 --> 00:20:57.800
It is still not quite like this.

00:20:57.800 --> 00:21:04.440
It is of the form s minus some
constant square over constant

00:21:04.440 --> 00:21:06.930
plus x square over
constant equals 1.

00:21:06.930 --> 00:21:11.850
That is still in ellipse, but
a displaced ellipse, right?

00:21:11.850 --> 00:21:15.300
What this really means
is that the ellipse

00:21:15.300 --> 00:21:19.120
is centered at this location.

00:21:19.120 --> 00:21:21.860
OK, this comes from
the displacement term

00:21:21.860 --> 00:21:23.560
in the square.

00:21:23.560 --> 00:21:26.380
And the eccentricity of
the ellipse-- that is,

00:21:26.380 --> 00:21:30.130
the size of the minor axis
relative to the major axis--

00:21:30.130 --> 00:21:33.710
is given by the inverse of
this quantity over here.

00:21:33.710 --> 00:21:36.430
So it is n minus
1 over n plus 1f.

00:21:36.430 --> 00:21:39.310
What is interesting to note
is that the focal point

00:21:39.310 --> 00:21:43.160
is to the right hand side of
the center of the ellipse.

00:21:43.160 --> 00:21:48.040
And in fact, this happens to be
the focal point of the ellipse.

00:21:48.040 --> 00:21:50.600
If you look at the
definition of an ellipse

00:21:50.600 --> 00:21:54.160
in the form of pure
geometry, ellipses

00:21:54.160 --> 00:21:57.610
are characterized
by two focal points.

00:21:57.610 --> 00:22:01.660
And it turns out in this
case, the focus of the rays

00:22:01.660 --> 00:22:03.438
is one of the focal
points of the ellipse.

00:22:03.438 --> 00:22:04.980
And that, of course,
is symmetrically

00:22:04.980 --> 00:22:06.630
located on the other side.

00:22:06.630 --> 00:22:12.420
OK, so this is a bit of
a mathematical trickery.

00:22:12.420 --> 00:22:14.640
But what I want to
emphasize, which is actually

00:22:14.640 --> 00:22:17.760
kind of important to know,
is that the focal point

00:22:17.760 --> 00:22:20.910
is actually past the
center of the ellipse.

00:22:28.210 --> 00:22:29.340
That's about it, really.

00:22:36.860 --> 00:22:41.810
The result of this is sort
of an ideal elliptical shape.

00:22:41.810 --> 00:22:43.700
That's something
worth remembering.

00:22:43.700 --> 00:22:51.860
That if you have a ideal
set of parallel rays coming

00:22:51.860 --> 00:22:53.780
in-- or as we will call
it a little bit later,

00:22:53.780 --> 00:22:54.930
a plane wave--

00:22:54.930 --> 00:22:59.450
and we wish to focus it at
the final distance inside

00:22:59.450 --> 00:23:00.710
of the electric material.

00:23:00.710 --> 00:23:02.750
The best possible
shape to achieve

00:23:02.750 --> 00:23:05.333
that is an elliptical shape.

00:23:05.333 --> 00:23:06.500
Now, again, there's caveats.

00:23:06.500 --> 00:23:09.410
For example, if I tilt
this incoming ray,

00:23:09.410 --> 00:23:11.940
then the focus will not
be perfect out here.

00:23:11.940 --> 00:23:15.230
So this is the same situation
as in the parabol line.

00:23:15.230 --> 00:23:18.500
It only works so
nice and so perfectly

00:23:18.500 --> 00:23:21.620
if the incidence
is exactly normal.

00:23:24.130 --> 00:23:28.290
Out of curiosity,
can anybody imagine--

00:23:28.290 --> 00:23:31.020
so if you compare this
with a paraboloid,

00:23:31.020 --> 00:23:32.580
one obvious advantage
is, of course,

00:23:32.580 --> 00:23:35.770
that I'm not blocking
the light path anymore.

00:23:35.770 --> 00:23:40.223
What is a possible disadvantage
of this kind of approach?

00:23:40.223 --> 00:23:41.390
There are several, actually.

00:23:41.390 --> 00:23:42.410
Tell me at least one.

00:23:42.410 --> 00:23:43.730
Yeah.

00:23:43.730 --> 00:23:46.646
Push the button.

00:23:46.646 --> 00:23:49.202
AUDIENCE: The detector
is inside the vector.

00:23:49.202 --> 00:23:51.410
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: That's
one obvious disadvantage.

00:23:51.410 --> 00:23:53.420
If I wanted to
really use this, I

00:23:53.420 --> 00:23:55.020
would have to put
the detector here.

00:23:55.020 --> 00:23:57.250
And, of course, it doesn't
have to be a full ellipse.

00:23:57.250 --> 00:23:59.930
I can always clip the
ellipse over here.

00:23:59.930 --> 00:24:02.720
The rays have no way of knowing
that this happened to them,

00:24:02.720 --> 00:24:05.250
so I can always stick
the detector over here.

00:24:05.250 --> 00:24:07.580
So maybe I can
overcome that problem.

00:24:07.580 --> 00:24:09.510
But it is a problem, yeah.

00:24:09.510 --> 00:24:13.340
What is the second problem
that kind of is sticking out?

00:24:19.143 --> 00:24:20.560
AUDIENCE: In the
case of if you're

00:24:20.560 --> 00:24:22.268
trying to build a
telescope, or something

00:24:22.268 --> 00:24:24.070
where you have to worry
about the structure

00:24:24.070 --> 00:24:26.000
of your optical setup.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:28.000
You could think that maybe
a solid element would

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:30.310
be much more bulky
or hard to abrogate

00:24:30.310 --> 00:24:34.730
than a reflecting
element, like paraboloid?

00:24:34.730 --> 00:24:36.870
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
That's correct.

00:24:36.870 --> 00:24:39.480
If you tried to
make a big element,

00:24:39.480 --> 00:24:42.630
a big lens, a big
focusing concentrator,

00:24:42.630 --> 00:24:45.542
like a solid concentrate,
or a satellite dish.

00:24:45.542 --> 00:24:47.250
That's a very inconvenient
shape to have.

00:24:47.250 --> 00:24:50.520
It is heavy--
absolutely, I agree.

00:24:50.520 --> 00:24:52.319
Tell me a third disadvantage.

00:25:00.470 --> 00:25:06.190
The paraboloid can go
on a very long distance.

00:25:06.190 --> 00:25:10.870
This one is a finite shape
because it's an ellipse.

00:25:10.870 --> 00:25:14.410
As it curves at some point, it
will reach a derivative equal

00:25:14.410 --> 00:25:15.220
to zero.

00:25:15.220 --> 00:25:16.460
It will stop there.

00:25:16.460 --> 00:25:19.540
So basically, this element
captures only a finite set

00:25:19.540 --> 00:25:22.880
of rays up to the minor
axis of the ellipse.

00:25:22.880 --> 00:25:25.570
It is missing the rest.

00:25:25.570 --> 00:25:29.770
Tell me a fourth and final
disadvantage of this setup

00:25:29.770 --> 00:25:31.350
that at least I could think of.

00:25:36.510 --> 00:25:39.190
I'll give you a hint.

00:25:39.190 --> 00:25:43.255
Last time, Piper did a very
nice demonstration with a prism.

00:25:46.447 --> 00:25:48.530
Do you remember something
that his demonstration--

00:25:52.270 --> 00:25:55.060
something about this
demonstration [INAUDIBLE]..

00:25:55.060 --> 00:25:57.970
AUDIENCE: There can be
total internal reflection.

00:25:57.970 --> 00:26:00.168
Like on this

00:26:00.168 --> 00:26:01.585
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
[INAUDIBLE]..

00:26:01.585 --> 00:26:04.815
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:26:04.815 --> 00:26:07.190
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Is there
a possibility for PIR here?

00:26:11.475 --> 00:26:12.850
AUDIENCE: The
index of refraction

00:26:12.850 --> 00:26:15.144
isn't necessarily the
same for all wavelengths?

00:26:16.687 --> 00:26:18.770
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: So
first of all, let's answer

00:26:18.770 --> 00:26:21.090
the previous question.

00:26:21.090 --> 00:26:25.640
Here, you're right to think
about the possibility of PIR.

00:26:25.640 --> 00:26:28.440
But if you look at it in
a little bit more detail,

00:26:28.440 --> 00:26:31.830
you will see that PIR is
not a problem in this case.

00:26:31.830 --> 00:26:34.860
At least for the rays
going up to here,

00:26:34.860 --> 00:26:37.040
there's no problem of PIR.

00:26:37.040 --> 00:26:40.520
Because the rays
come from a low index

00:26:40.520 --> 00:26:42.860
medium to a high index medium.

00:26:42.860 --> 00:26:48.020
And therefore, they will always
refract inside the [INAUDIBLE]..

00:26:48.020 --> 00:26:50.980
What is interesting to
happen to the ray that

00:26:50.980 --> 00:26:55.100
is incident exactly tangential
to the ellipse over here.

00:26:55.100 --> 00:26:57.290
It will still be refracted,
if you think about it.

00:26:57.290 --> 00:26:58.370
It's Snell's law.

00:26:58.370 --> 00:27:01.100
And it will give you sort
of the maximum acceptance

00:27:01.100 --> 00:27:05.840
cone of the interface that
we discussed last week,

00:27:05.840 --> 00:27:10.130
I mean, on Monday in
relation to Snell's law.

00:27:10.130 --> 00:27:13.000
So then out of the two demos
that Piper did last week,

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:15.110
the PIR is not the problem.

00:27:15.110 --> 00:27:17.330
It is the other one, as
you correctly pointed out.

00:27:17.330 --> 00:27:18.890
So you want to repeat?

00:27:18.890 --> 00:27:19.840
Who has spoken before?

00:27:24.100 --> 00:27:26.025
Someone mentioned the
index of refraction.

00:27:26.025 --> 00:27:27.400
AUDIENCE: The
index of refraction

00:27:27.400 --> 00:27:30.350
isn't the same for
all wavelengths.

00:27:30.350 --> 00:27:32.618
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
That's right.

00:27:32.618 --> 00:27:33.160
That's right.

00:27:33.160 --> 00:27:35.770
So since the index
of refraction is not

00:27:35.770 --> 00:27:37.960
the same for all
wavelengths, what this means

00:27:37.960 --> 00:27:41.590
is that the focal distance
now becomes a function

00:27:41.590 --> 00:27:43.420
of the index of refraction.

00:27:43.420 --> 00:27:45.340
And I may tune it.

00:27:45.340 --> 00:27:47.630
Basically, what I do is
I manufacture this shape.

00:27:47.630 --> 00:27:50.560
So I can manufacture
it for a certain index

00:27:50.560 --> 00:27:51.990
for a standard wavelength.

00:27:51.990 --> 00:27:53.990
If the index changes,
this relation

00:27:53.990 --> 00:27:57.400
will not be satisfied
anymore, and therefore

00:27:57.400 --> 00:28:01.690
the refractive element
will become imperfect.

00:28:01.690 --> 00:28:05.590
How do we call this phenomenon
of dependence of index

00:28:05.590 --> 00:28:10.100
of refraction on wavelength?

00:28:10.100 --> 00:28:12.290
Dispersion.

00:28:12.290 --> 00:28:13.250
Dispersion.

00:28:13.250 --> 00:28:18.060
And in the context that
we're discussing here.

00:28:18.060 --> 00:28:21.010
OK, it is dispersion.

00:28:21.010 --> 00:28:23.410
In the context of
focusing, when we

00:28:23.410 --> 00:28:28.070
get imperfect focusing
because of dispersion,

00:28:28.070 --> 00:28:30.050
It has also another
special name.

00:28:30.050 --> 00:28:35.246
It is called
chromatic aberration.

00:28:38.650 --> 00:28:42.480
The term aberration we'll
see again in the next hour.

00:28:42.480 --> 00:28:45.940
It generally refers to
failures of optical systems

00:28:45.940 --> 00:28:48.640
to focus light as
they're supposed to.

00:28:48.640 --> 00:28:51.380
So this is the first such
failure that we encounter.

00:28:51.380 --> 00:28:53.660
The term chromatic, I have
an advantage over you.

00:28:53.660 --> 00:28:54.440
I'm Greek.

00:28:54.440 --> 00:28:57.640
And this turns out
to be a Greek word.

00:28:57.640 --> 00:29:02.780
Chroma in Greek means color.

00:29:02.780 --> 00:29:04.630
And this is the Greek spelling.

00:29:04.630 --> 00:29:08.090
If you want to spell it out in
Latin so you can pronounce it,

00:29:08.090 --> 00:29:09.400
it is chroma.

00:29:09.400 --> 00:29:12.550
And that's where the word
chromatic is derived from.

00:29:12.550 --> 00:29:15.010
It literally means
separation due to color.

00:29:18.370 --> 00:29:21.680
Any questions on
any of this so far?

00:29:33.570 --> 00:29:34.820
I'm sorry, there's a question.

00:29:34.820 --> 00:29:42.020
AUDIENCE: If someone thought
of a lenslike element

00:29:42.020 --> 00:29:43.880
in which the
focusing takes place

00:29:43.880 --> 00:29:47.130
on the other side
of the element.

00:29:47.130 --> 00:29:49.495
Will it have a
[INAUDIBLE] power surface?

00:29:51.880 --> 00:29:53.880
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
That's coming up, actually,

00:29:53.880 --> 00:29:55.420
in a few slides.

00:29:55.420 --> 00:29:59.530
So yeah, I mean, the answer
to your question is generally,

00:29:59.530 --> 00:30:04.330
if you want to focus
a point from the left

00:30:04.330 --> 00:30:07.030
to a point on the right, at
the opposite side of element.

00:30:07.030 --> 00:30:10.180
You need two hyperbolic surface.

00:30:10.180 --> 00:30:12.880
I'll cover that in a second.

00:30:12.880 --> 00:30:15.940
Of course, hyperbolas are
difficult to manufacture.

00:30:15.940 --> 00:30:19.690
People typically make
spherical surfaces.

00:30:19.690 --> 00:30:22.550
You can also have a sphere,
nowadays, by injection molding.

00:30:22.550 --> 00:30:26.050
I will go into that also later.

00:30:26.050 --> 00:30:30.220
But even that is only
perfect for on axis points.

00:30:30.220 --> 00:30:33.100
If you move points off
axis, then it fails again.

00:30:33.100 --> 00:30:37.910
So it becomes the whole
problem of optical design.

00:30:37.910 --> 00:30:42.270
OK, so I will switch now
to today's, actually,

00:30:42.270 --> 00:30:43.050
set of lectures.

00:30:52.110 --> 00:30:54.830
And you realized that
we were kind of behind

00:30:54.830 --> 00:30:56.090
by almost one lecture.

00:30:56.090 --> 00:30:58.340
I think we're beginning
to catch up now.

00:30:58.340 --> 00:31:01.400
But what I would like to do
today for the rest of the two

00:31:01.400 --> 00:31:05.360
hours that you have is
to go relatively slowly

00:31:05.360 --> 00:31:11.100
over a number of
different topics, which

00:31:11.100 --> 00:31:12.780
are also related to focusing.

00:31:12.780 --> 00:31:15.610
But as we go along,
we will generalize

00:31:15.610 --> 00:31:18.795
focusing to more and more
complicated situations.

00:31:18.795 --> 00:31:20.670
So I wanted to solve
two cases of-- actually,

00:31:20.670 --> 00:31:24.060
one case of focusing using two
different types of elements,

00:31:24.060 --> 00:31:27.850
a reflector and a refractor.

00:31:27.850 --> 00:31:30.700
In order to make this stuff
a little bit more specific,

00:31:30.700 --> 00:31:33.340
let me remind you
of some definitions

00:31:33.340 --> 00:31:37.420
that we discussed a little
bit at the first lecture.

00:31:37.420 --> 00:31:41.200
But I would like to remind you
again with a bit more detail.

00:31:41.200 --> 00:31:45.780
So what is the concept
of a spherical wave.

00:31:45.780 --> 00:31:49.460
So spherical wave
is what you get

00:31:49.460 --> 00:31:53.150
if you have light or
originating at the point source.

00:31:53.150 --> 00:31:56.085
It is also referred
to as a point object.

00:31:56.085 --> 00:31:57.710
So what happens then
is you get the fan

00:31:57.710 --> 00:31:59.960
of rays that is divergent.

00:31:59.960 --> 00:32:04.220
And if you plug the normals
to these rays, these normals,

00:32:04.220 --> 00:32:07.200
they look like spheres.

00:32:07.200 --> 00:32:10.590
So, of course, the wavefronts
expand as the spherical wave

00:32:10.590 --> 00:32:13.110
propagates.

00:32:13.110 --> 00:32:17.820
And because these wavefronts
are spherical surfaces,

00:32:17.820 --> 00:32:21.690
that's why we call
it a spherical wave.

00:32:21.690 --> 00:32:23.870
Again, very important to
remember by definition.

00:32:23.870 --> 00:32:27.260
The wavefront is
normal to the rays.

00:32:27.260 --> 00:32:31.550
So what I have done here in
principle is I took each ray.

00:32:31.550 --> 00:32:33.830
I computed the
normal to the ray.

00:32:33.830 --> 00:32:38.060
I connected all the normals,
and I get this sphere over here.

00:32:38.060 --> 00:32:40.520
I don't know if I did it very
well in my graphic over here,

00:32:40.520 --> 00:32:43.820
but that's what this
is supposed to denote.

00:32:43.820 --> 00:32:48.970
OK, you can flip this
situation and create

00:32:48.970 --> 00:32:52.040
a convergent spherical
wave, where basically, you

00:32:52.040 --> 00:32:57.150
have rays that are
propagating towards the point.

00:32:57.150 --> 00:32:59.490
If that is the case, it is
not a point source anymore.

00:32:59.490 --> 00:33:00.930
You call it a point image.

00:33:03.510 --> 00:33:06.870
In most optical systems-- at
least in optical systems that

00:33:06.870 --> 00:33:08.850
we will consider here--

00:33:08.850 --> 00:33:10.860
this is really the goal
of an optical system.

00:33:10.860 --> 00:33:14.460
You try to take
rays of light that

00:33:14.460 --> 00:33:18.120
are given to you by some
source that you do not control,

00:33:18.120 --> 00:33:21.530
such as an object, or a
star far out of reach.

00:33:21.530 --> 00:33:24.280
And what you try to do is you
try to arrange your optics,

00:33:24.280 --> 00:33:27.130
select your lenses,
space them appropriately,

00:33:27.130 --> 00:33:28.480
and so on and so forth.

00:33:28.480 --> 00:33:32.280
So that you can converge
these incoming rays

00:33:32.280 --> 00:33:34.810
into point images.

00:33:34.810 --> 00:33:42.130
So if you wish this is our
given, or our customer.

00:33:42.130 --> 00:33:44.000
And then this is what
the customer wants.

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:47.860
The customer wants
to form point images.

00:33:47.860 --> 00:33:51.380
So a good deal of working
the field of optics

00:33:51.380 --> 00:33:56.390
has to do with this
problem, how you can image--

00:33:56.390 --> 00:33:58.820
however you can
create point images.

00:33:58.820 --> 00:34:00.530
I'll take this out,
because it does not

00:34:00.530 --> 00:34:01.880
relate to this discussion.

00:34:01.880 --> 00:34:03.850
OK.

00:34:03.850 --> 00:34:05.860
So again, the
wavefronts are spherical

00:34:05.860 --> 00:34:10.427
here with a common center
at the point image.

00:34:10.427 --> 00:34:12.219
But in this case, of
course, the wavefronts

00:34:12.219 --> 00:34:14.710
are contracting as you go
towards the point image,

00:34:14.710 --> 00:34:17.350
because the rays are converging.

00:34:17.350 --> 00:34:21.820
And, of course, [AUDIO OUT]
wavefronts ideally collapse

00:34:21.820 --> 00:34:23.010
into a point.

00:34:23.010 --> 00:34:24.820
This doesn't sound
very physical.

00:34:24.820 --> 00:34:31.030
And a little bit later, when we
do the theory of diffraction.

00:34:31.030 --> 00:34:34.790
We will see in a bit more detail
what happens at that point.

00:34:34.790 --> 00:34:38.530
It is not really that the
wavefront ideally collapses.

00:34:38.530 --> 00:34:40.659
Something else happens
that we will see.

00:34:40.659 --> 00:34:43.330
Within the geometrical
optics approximation,

00:34:43.330 --> 00:34:45.850
let's accept it for now
that this is the case.

00:34:45.850 --> 00:34:48.550
That indeed, the rays can
converge to a single point,

00:34:48.550 --> 00:34:52.980
and then the wavefront
over there collapses.

00:34:52.980 --> 00:34:58.750
OK, this is true for pretty
much every case of imaging.

00:34:58.750 --> 00:35:01.770
However, in a number
of situations,

00:35:01.770 --> 00:35:04.940
it is very convenient
to take one extreme case

00:35:04.940 --> 00:35:10.920
where the point source, or the
point object is very far away.

00:35:10.920 --> 00:35:13.530
I mentioned that already
about half an hour ago.

00:35:13.530 --> 00:35:17.100
And I called it the
point source of infinity,

00:35:17.100 --> 00:35:18.810
or a point object of infinity.

00:35:18.810 --> 00:35:21.570
A very good approximation
for that is a star.

00:35:21.570 --> 00:35:25.288
If we look at stars in the night
sky, they look like points.

00:35:25.288 --> 00:35:26.580
Of course, a star is humongous.

00:35:26.580 --> 00:35:29.610
It is probably thousands of
times bigger than the earth.

00:35:29.610 --> 00:35:33.480
But because it is at a distance
of thousands or millions

00:35:33.480 --> 00:35:35.640
of light years away,
it appears to us

00:35:35.640 --> 00:35:38.340
to be like a point,
a point source.

00:35:38.340 --> 00:35:40.640
So again, there's another
important point to emphasize.

00:35:40.640 --> 00:35:43.260
When we talk about the
point object at infinity,

00:35:43.260 --> 00:35:46.580
we don't necessarily imply
that it is mathematically

00:35:46.580 --> 00:35:48.560
a point, that is, it
has zero dimension.

00:35:48.560 --> 00:35:50.690
What we really mean
is it is so far

00:35:50.690 --> 00:35:54.980
away that the angle that
I subtend towards that

00:35:54.980 --> 00:35:57.380
far away point is minimal.

00:35:57.380 --> 00:35:59.870
If that is true, if
that assumption is true,

00:35:59.870 --> 00:36:01.610
then I can call it a point.

00:36:01.610 --> 00:36:04.620
I mean, I can call it a
point source at infinity.

00:36:04.620 --> 00:36:08.100
And what happens if you
really went near that point

00:36:08.100 --> 00:36:11.570
far at infinity, you would
still see divergent rays.

00:36:11.570 --> 00:36:14.660
But because these rays propagate
at a very long distance,

00:36:14.660 --> 00:36:18.440
you only get to see the
set of rays near the axis

00:36:18.440 --> 00:36:20.128
that departed from that point.

00:36:20.128 --> 00:36:21.920
And because you're
[INAUDIBLE],, these rays

00:36:21.920 --> 00:36:26.750
are really tightly collapsed
near the central ray over here.

00:36:26.750 --> 00:36:29.760
They all look parallel.

00:36:29.760 --> 00:36:32.700
So a set of rays that I
propagate and they're parallel.

00:36:32.700 --> 00:36:36.070
Like so on here, we
call it a plane wave.

00:36:36.070 --> 00:36:38.520
If you go back to your notes
from the first lecture,

00:36:38.520 --> 00:36:44.030
we called it the plane wave,
or the planar wavefront.

00:36:44.030 --> 00:36:46.280
But we can also call it--

00:36:46.280 --> 00:36:48.200
parallel [INAUDIBLE]
rays, we can also

00:36:48.200 --> 00:36:52.215
call it an object at infinity.

00:36:57.280 --> 00:36:59.230
Of course, because
the rays are parallel.

00:36:59.230 --> 00:37:03.130
If I draw the normals to
them, they will form planes.

00:37:03.130 --> 00:37:05.670
They form ideal planar surfaces.

00:37:05.670 --> 00:37:07.830
And that's why this
is called the planar

00:37:07.830 --> 00:37:11.290
wavefront, or a plane wave.

00:37:11.290 --> 00:37:14.377
For our purposes, the
two terms are identical.

00:37:14.377 --> 00:37:16.210
And, of course, this
goes the other way too.

00:37:16.210 --> 00:37:20.650
If I had a planar wave
also propagating like this.

00:37:20.650 --> 00:37:26.980
I can also claim that I create
a point image at infinity.

00:37:26.980 --> 00:37:29.170
Because if I take
parallel lines and I

00:37:29.170 --> 00:37:32.140
propagate them for an
infinitely long distance.

00:37:32.140 --> 00:37:34.520
OK, what I'm about to say is
not mathematically correct,

00:37:34.520 --> 00:37:36.850
but in optics, we
say it all the time.

00:37:36.850 --> 00:37:39.460
It is that these parallel
rays will meet at infinity.

00:37:39.460 --> 00:37:42.040
Of course, parallel
rays never meet.

00:37:42.040 --> 00:37:44.810
But you can simply to
justify it in your mind,

00:37:44.810 --> 00:37:46.640
flip to this picture,
and take these rays,

00:37:46.640 --> 00:37:49.300
propagate them backwards.

00:37:49.300 --> 00:37:51.003
At a very, very
far away distance,

00:37:51.003 --> 00:37:53.170
you cannot tell the difference,
whether they started

00:37:53.170 --> 00:37:57.640
as parallel rays, or they
started as a tightly convergent

00:37:57.640 --> 00:37:59.930
small ray bundle.

00:37:59.930 --> 00:38:05.560
OK, so this [AUDIO OUT]
because very often,

00:38:05.560 --> 00:38:09.520
it simplifies
calculations and gives

00:38:09.520 --> 00:38:11.590
certain kinds of intuition.

00:38:11.590 --> 00:38:15.145
And again, we define it in
the geometric optic sense.

00:38:18.230 --> 00:38:21.300
When we do diffraction
about a month from now,

00:38:21.300 --> 00:38:24.020
we will define it more
rigorously in a way

00:38:24.020 --> 00:38:27.260
that is probably much more
convincing than I do now.

00:38:27.260 --> 00:38:29.480
The reason I'm apologizing
for this definition

00:38:29.480 --> 00:38:32.870
is that there's no such thing
as mathematical infinity

00:38:32.870 --> 00:38:33.600
in real life.

00:38:33.600 --> 00:38:36.380
Even a star, it is a
very long distance away,

00:38:36.380 --> 00:38:38.970
but it is not an
infinite distance away.

00:38:38.970 --> 00:38:40.360
So what do I mean by infinity?

00:38:40.360 --> 00:38:44.340
For example, [INAUDIBLE],, who is
sitting here on the front row.

00:38:44.340 --> 00:38:46.760
Is he at infinity with
respect to me, or no?

00:38:46.760 --> 00:38:50.620
Well, what about you guys who
are sitting in the cam bridge?

00:38:50.620 --> 00:38:52.610
Well, OK, the surface
of the earth is curved,

00:38:52.610 --> 00:38:54.633
so that creates an
obvious problem.

00:38:54.633 --> 00:38:56.300
But suppose I could
draw a straight line

00:38:56.300 --> 00:38:59.120
through the center of the
earth from Singapore to Boston.

00:38:59.120 --> 00:39:01.950
Would you guys be at
infinity with respect to me?

00:39:01.950 --> 00:39:05.760
OK, it actually depends on
a lot of different things.

00:39:05.760 --> 00:39:09.980
It depends on the relative
sizes that I have and you have.

00:39:09.980 --> 00:39:12.933
It depends on the wavelength
that the light is propagating.

00:39:12.933 --> 00:39:14.600
And actually, that's
about it, according

00:39:14.600 --> 00:39:15.680
to diffraction theory.

00:39:15.680 --> 00:39:19.030
So we will see a rigorous
definition of what is infinity

00:39:19.030 --> 00:39:20.450
when we do diffraction.

00:39:20.450 --> 00:39:23.930
For now, let's take
it on faith that if I

00:39:23.930 --> 00:39:26.630
have a set of rays that
appear [AUDIO OUT],,

00:39:26.630 --> 00:39:32.680
we'll call it image of infinity.

00:39:32.680 --> 00:39:35.210
So sometimes, we use
the term collimated.

00:39:38.642 --> 00:39:39.600
That's a better marker.

00:39:42.320 --> 00:39:45.550
Collimated rays.

00:39:45.550 --> 00:39:49.280
So collimated is from
the word colinear, right?

00:39:49.280 --> 00:39:52.500
Creating parallel to each other.

00:39:52.500 --> 00:39:54.850
OK.

00:39:54.850 --> 00:39:59.610
So I included this slide,
but as a reminder, and that

00:39:59.610 --> 00:40:03.060
as a reference,
because for the next--

00:40:03.060 --> 00:40:06.300
I don't know, for the next
semester really, from now on,

00:40:06.300 --> 00:40:07.850
we'll be using
these terms a lot.

00:40:07.850 --> 00:40:11.610
Spherical waves, plane
waves, spherical wavefronts,

00:40:11.610 --> 00:40:13.960
and so on and so forth.

00:40:13.960 --> 00:40:16.920
The concept of
infinity applies to

00:40:16.920 --> 00:40:20.810
both convergent and divergent
spherical waves at infinity.

00:40:25.860 --> 00:40:27.350
All right.

00:40:27.350 --> 00:40:32.780
So the two examples that
we saw at the beginning.

00:40:32.780 --> 00:40:36.730
These are basically examples
of imaging sources at infinity.

00:40:36.730 --> 00:40:38.620
Because we had
plane waves coming

00:40:38.620 --> 00:40:43.210
into the paraboloidal
reflector and ellipsoidal

00:40:43.210 --> 00:40:45.890
refractor respectively.

00:40:45.890 --> 00:40:47.410
And then these two
elements managed

00:40:47.410 --> 00:40:52.660
to convert these plane
waves, these parallel

00:40:52.660 --> 00:40:59.690
ray bundles into perfect
converging spherical waves.

00:40:59.690 --> 00:41:03.290
Therefore, they created
perfect point images

00:41:03.290 --> 00:41:05.810
at the corresponding
focal points.

00:41:05.810 --> 00:41:07.370
And then wavefronts,
I also put down

00:41:07.370 --> 00:41:14.050
the two equations, the
equations of the two elements.

00:41:14.050 --> 00:41:21.920
Now, let's flip the coin
a little bit, and ask

00:41:21.920 --> 00:41:26.550
how can I create a
point image at infinity?

00:41:26.550 --> 00:41:29.910
Now, I start with a point
source that is within my range.

00:41:29.910 --> 00:41:31.770
Here is my point source.

00:41:31.770 --> 00:41:33.380
Here is my point source.

00:41:33.380 --> 00:41:36.770
And I'm trying to
create an image

00:41:36.770 --> 00:41:38.415
of that source of infinity.

00:41:38.415 --> 00:41:40.790
Well, another way to say it
is that what I'm trying to do

00:41:40.790 --> 00:41:46.150
is I'm trying to
collimate the light.

00:41:52.050 --> 00:41:53.520
So in the case of
the paraboloid,

00:41:53.520 --> 00:41:55.780
it's actually very simple.

00:41:55.780 --> 00:41:59.580
All I have to do is reverse
the paths of the rays.

00:41:59.580 --> 00:42:02.190
This may also sound arbitrary,
but in electromagnetics,

00:42:02.190 --> 00:42:05.940
there's a very basic principle
that says that you can do that.

00:42:05.940 --> 00:42:07.990
I will not go into
that in detail,

00:42:07.990 --> 00:42:11.370
but I can assure you that from
the rigorous electromagnetic

00:42:11.370 --> 00:42:13.560
point of view, this
is permissible.

00:42:13.560 --> 00:42:17.190
You can reverse the ray
paths, and you still

00:42:17.190 --> 00:42:19.310
get the value of the
electromagnetic field.

00:42:19.310 --> 00:42:23.010
Therefore, a paraboloidal
reflector works both ways.

00:42:23.010 --> 00:42:25.620
You can use it
either as a receiver,

00:42:25.620 --> 00:42:27.870
so you can focus a
source at infinity,

00:42:27.870 --> 00:42:29.813
and you can detect it here.

00:42:29.813 --> 00:42:30.730
Or it's a transmitter.

00:42:30.730 --> 00:42:33.870
You can have a point source
at this finite distance,

00:42:33.870 --> 00:42:38.723
and you can broadcast a number
of cars, but you can beam it.

00:42:38.723 --> 00:42:39.390
That's the word.

00:42:39.390 --> 00:42:43.320
You can beam it
to a very narrow--

00:42:43.320 --> 00:42:46.810
to a target that is at a
very long distance away.

00:42:49.690 --> 00:42:58.030
In the case of a refractor,
the answer is not as simple.

00:42:58.030 --> 00:43:05.390
Because in the process of
reversing the situation,

00:43:05.390 --> 00:43:09.950
now, the source is in air.

00:43:09.950 --> 00:43:14.360
And the collimated light is in
glass, is in the dielectric.

00:43:14.360 --> 00:43:16.700
So therefore, the ellipse
doesn't necessarily

00:43:16.700 --> 00:43:19.180
provide the same answer anymore.

00:43:19.180 --> 00:43:21.380
So basically, you have to
solve the problem again.

00:43:21.380 --> 00:43:23.360
And indeed, we find
that the ellipse is not

00:43:23.360 --> 00:43:25.260
the answer in this case.

00:43:25.260 --> 00:43:26.690
The answer is a hyperbola.

00:43:26.690 --> 00:43:29.010
A hyperboloidal surface.

00:43:29.010 --> 00:43:30.790
Given by this
equation over here.

00:43:30.790 --> 00:43:32.800
If you compare it with
the case of the ellipse,

00:43:32.800 --> 00:43:34.813
the difference is a minus sign.

00:43:34.813 --> 00:43:36.480
So again, I will not
do this derivation.

00:43:36.480 --> 00:43:38.400
I will let you do
it by yourselves

00:43:38.400 --> 00:43:39.740
if you have the inclination.

00:43:39.740 --> 00:43:44.570
Or if we have time at the
end today, we might do it.

00:43:44.570 --> 00:43:45.870
It's a very similar derivation.

00:43:45.870 --> 00:43:47.760
We apply Fermat's principle.

00:43:47.760 --> 00:43:50.430
We basically demand
that the path

00:43:50.430 --> 00:43:54.660
from here to some reference
point equals the path from here

00:43:54.660 --> 00:43:58.800
to the same reference
plane off axis.

00:43:58.800 --> 00:44:00.390
When you apply
this principle, you

00:44:00.390 --> 00:44:06.640
end up with this equation after
some algebraic manipulation.

00:44:06.640 --> 00:44:08.802
So the word confusion.

00:44:08.802 --> 00:44:11.890
I actually put
together a table that

00:44:11.890 --> 00:44:15.580
contains all the
possible cases of first

00:44:15.580 --> 00:44:22.140
of all, reflective versus
refractive focusing elements.

00:44:22.140 --> 00:44:26.550
And point sources, or
point images at infinity.

00:44:26.550 --> 00:44:29.550
And there's actually
six possible cases.

00:44:29.550 --> 00:44:32.700
For the kinds of a reflector,
we saw that it doesn't really

00:44:32.700 --> 00:44:33.450
make a difference.

00:44:33.450 --> 00:44:36.390
In both cases, a
paraboloid is the answer.

00:44:36.390 --> 00:44:40.320
Because I computed
already the focusing

00:44:40.320 --> 00:44:42.840
of an object at
infinity, which is

00:44:42.840 --> 00:44:46.020
focused at the focal
point of the paraboloid.

00:44:46.020 --> 00:44:48.610
And if I reverse the
rays, the same paraboloid

00:44:48.610 --> 00:44:52.880
will take a point source at
F, and image that point source

00:44:52.880 --> 00:44:54.150
at infinity.

00:44:54.150 --> 00:44:56.090
So that is very simple.

00:44:56.090 --> 00:44:59.740
In the case of a dielectric,
I can do two things.

00:44:59.740 --> 00:45:01.820
First of all, I start
with the ellipsoid.

00:45:01.820 --> 00:45:05.400
When we derive the
case of the ellipsoid,

00:45:05.400 --> 00:45:08.250
focusing a plane wave
coming from infinity.

00:45:08.250 --> 00:45:12.720
And we saw that it focuses at
the focal point of the ellipse,

00:45:12.720 --> 00:45:14.400
inside the ellipse.

00:45:14.400 --> 00:45:16.050
If I reverse the
array paths, then I

00:45:16.050 --> 00:45:18.570
have this situation where
the light originates

00:45:18.570 --> 00:45:20.030
at the center of the ellipse.

00:45:20.030 --> 00:45:22.470
And then it gets
collimated as it comes out.

00:45:22.470 --> 00:45:24.450
Now, the reason the
ellipse is still the answer

00:45:24.450 --> 00:45:28.830
here is because the light
starts at the dielectric.

00:45:28.830 --> 00:45:30.420
So really, now, I'm correct.

00:45:30.420 --> 00:45:32.400
I can still revise
the optical path,

00:45:32.400 --> 00:45:34.510
and I get the correct answer.

00:45:34.510 --> 00:45:39.950
So this has led to cases
of objects at infinity,

00:45:39.950 --> 00:45:42.090
and image at infinity.

00:45:42.090 --> 00:45:48.470
But have to be careful
that the object is in air.

00:45:48.470 --> 00:45:51.380
In this case, the object
of infinity is in air.

00:45:51.380 --> 00:45:53.810
The focus is inside
the dielectric.

00:45:53.810 --> 00:45:55.820
In this case, the
source of the object

00:45:55.820 --> 00:45:59.030
is inside the dielectric,
and the image at infinity

00:45:59.030 --> 00:45:59.870
is in air.

00:46:02.710 --> 00:46:04.540
The other case is
the one that I just

00:46:04.540 --> 00:46:07.000
mentioned, and did
not derive, but I

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:08.840
let you derive by yourselves.

00:46:08.840 --> 00:46:10.810
And that is the case
of a source that

00:46:10.810 --> 00:46:12.770
is now at a finite distance.

00:46:12.770 --> 00:46:17.530
And I wish the image to be at
infinity inside the dielectric.

00:46:17.530 --> 00:46:22.250
So this case, this is
hyperboloidal surface.

00:46:22.250 --> 00:46:23.753
And, of course, you
might ask, well,

00:46:23.753 --> 00:46:25.170
what the heck does
it really mean?

00:46:25.170 --> 00:46:29.428
Can I really make an
infinitely large refractor?

00:46:29.428 --> 00:46:31.470
Well, that says you don't
have to, because if any

00:46:31.470 --> 00:46:33.940
of the refractor is cut here.

00:46:33.940 --> 00:46:36.770
Since the rays are
coming out normal,

00:46:36.770 --> 00:46:38.860
they do not refract at
all at this interface.

00:46:38.860 --> 00:46:42.700
So really, you can
chop the hyperbola,

00:46:42.700 --> 00:46:47.890
and then you can still have your
point, your image at infinity.

00:46:47.890 --> 00:46:49.090
So that's fine.

00:46:49.090 --> 00:46:51.642
And, of course, you can also
reverse the ray paths here.

00:46:51.642 --> 00:46:53.350
And you can create
the opposite situation

00:46:53.350 --> 00:46:55.720
where whenever you have
an object at infinity,

00:46:55.720 --> 00:46:57.820
but inside the dielectric.

00:46:57.820 --> 00:47:01.632
And you have a point image
at a finite distance in air.

00:47:01.632 --> 00:47:03.340
And that could also
be hyperbolic, right?

00:47:03.340 --> 00:47:08.200
Because this, I derive simply
by flipping the ray paths

00:47:08.200 --> 00:47:09.320
from one case to the next.

