00:50:17.817 --> 00:50:19.650
But we'll say a little
bit about aberrations

00:50:19.650 --> 00:50:20.780
in the coming slides.

00:50:20.780 --> 00:50:22.810
So maybe you can postpone that.

00:50:27.260 --> 00:50:28.410
Any other questions?

00:50:36.740 --> 00:50:38.720
So speaking of aberrations,
here they come.

00:50:42.950 --> 00:50:45.910
First of all, let me say a few
things about the wavefronts.

00:50:45.910 --> 00:50:50.960
So by definition, I will
just look at this case,

00:50:50.960 --> 00:50:53.720
and then you can
construct similar diagrams

00:50:53.720 --> 00:50:57.298
for all the six cases that
were in the previous slide.

00:50:57.298 --> 00:50:58.340
I didn't want to do that.

00:50:58.340 --> 00:51:00.590
It actually takes a very
long time to do such a slide,

00:51:00.590 --> 00:51:03.210
so I didn't want
to do all of them.

00:51:03.210 --> 00:51:06.180
But this is pretty
representative.

00:51:06.180 --> 00:51:08.840
So it conveys the idea, I think.

00:51:08.840 --> 00:51:11.290
So by definition, we have
a plane wave coming in.

00:51:11.290 --> 00:51:14.960
So you have plane wavefronts
arriving at the interface.

00:51:14.960 --> 00:51:18.230
And also by definition,
because by construction

00:51:18.230 --> 00:51:23.200
we required all the rays,
all the refractive rays.

00:51:23.200 --> 00:51:26.720
They are required to meet at
the focal point over here.

00:51:26.720 --> 00:51:29.570
It means that what
we have inside

00:51:29.570 --> 00:51:33.890
the refractor is
converging spherical waves.

00:51:33.890 --> 00:51:38.130
And therefore, if you look at
the wavefronts collapsing in

00:51:38.130 --> 00:51:42.150
towards the focal point,
they are perfect spheres.

00:51:42.150 --> 00:51:46.180
This is all equal section,
so these are perfect spheres

00:51:46.180 --> 00:51:49.533
collapsing towards
uppercase F. It's

00:51:49.533 --> 00:51:51.450
kind of interesting to
think what happens here

00:51:51.450 --> 00:51:53.170
at the interface.

00:51:53.170 --> 00:51:55.900
So [INAUDIBLE] the interface,
you have two things happening.

00:51:55.900 --> 00:52:00.010
You have the ray arriving at
the left, then sort of being

00:52:00.010 --> 00:52:02.178
refracted into the sphere.

00:52:02.178 --> 00:52:03.595
But the wavelength
has to remain--

00:52:08.870 --> 00:52:11.120
well, it has to
remain continuous.

00:52:11.120 --> 00:52:13.190
So basically, what
happens is the wavefronts,

00:52:13.190 --> 00:52:15.950
they curve in a continuous
fashion, as shown here.

00:52:20.440 --> 00:52:25.320
You can think of it basically
as the wave approaches

00:52:25.320 --> 00:52:28.490
from the left toward
the refractor,

00:52:28.490 --> 00:52:30.740
as it starts entering
the refractor, of course,

00:52:30.740 --> 00:52:32.840
it enters first at the apex.

00:52:32.840 --> 00:52:36.110
And then the wavefront
starts bulging.

00:52:36.110 --> 00:52:38.730
It sort of creates this bulge.

00:52:38.730 --> 00:52:41.270
And then as it goes
more and more in,

00:52:41.270 --> 00:52:49.130
the bulge progresses to create a
segment of a spherical surface.

00:52:49.130 --> 00:52:53.860
Now, you can justify that with
a number of different ways.

00:52:53.860 --> 00:52:57.190
One is, of course, Fermat's
principle that we just applied.

00:52:57.190 --> 00:52:59.370
The other is if you
think that light actually

00:52:59.370 --> 00:53:05.100
propagates slower in this medium
than it propagates in air,

00:53:05.100 --> 00:53:07.770
then you can see why the
wavefront starts bulging here.

00:53:07.770 --> 00:53:12.300
Because as soon as the light
enters the medium, it gets

00:53:12.300 --> 00:53:13.230
slowed down.

00:53:13.230 --> 00:53:14.730
So now that portion
of the wavefront

00:53:14.730 --> 00:53:17.370
that is still outside
in air is actually

00:53:17.370 --> 00:53:20.370
faster than the
portion that is here.

00:53:20.370 --> 00:53:22.650
Even if you compare,
let's take this case.

00:53:22.650 --> 00:53:25.210
If you compare the portion
of the wavefront that is here

00:53:25.210 --> 00:53:28.280
at the apex to the
portion that is here,

00:53:28.280 --> 00:53:29.880
to the portion that is here.

00:53:29.880 --> 00:53:32.250
You can see that this one
has traveled the longer

00:53:32.250 --> 00:53:34.020
distance in the medium.

00:53:34.020 --> 00:53:36.330
So that's why it
is further behind.

00:53:36.330 --> 00:53:38.760
This one has traveled
slightly less,

00:53:38.760 --> 00:53:41.250
so therefore, it is a
little bit further ahead.

00:53:41.250 --> 00:53:45.360
And this one is still in air,
so it is even more ahead.

00:53:45.360 --> 00:53:47.010
So this is another
way to explain

00:53:47.010 --> 00:53:49.680
why the wavefronts
are bulging, and they

00:53:49.680 --> 00:53:52.380
become spherical as the
wave enters the medium.

00:53:56.200 --> 00:54:02.600
Now, of course, they
become exactly spherical.

00:54:02.600 --> 00:54:07.480
It's very special to
shape that we chose.

00:54:07.480 --> 00:54:10.600
Because we demanded
Fermat to hold,

00:54:10.600 --> 00:54:14.500
the wavefronts that
result from refraction

00:54:14.500 --> 00:54:16.310
of this elliptical interface.

00:54:16.310 --> 00:54:18.010
They actually become spherical.

00:54:18.010 --> 00:54:20.260
But you can easily
convince yourself

00:54:20.260 --> 00:54:22.410
that if I chose a
different surface.

00:54:22.410 --> 00:54:25.490
Say, if I chose a
sphere or a hyperbola

00:54:25.490 --> 00:54:30.650
in this case, or some crazy
polynomial, quartic, sixth

00:54:30.650 --> 00:54:34.460
order, I don't know,
some generalized surface.

00:54:34.460 --> 00:54:36.430
Then the wavefronts
that we get here.

00:54:36.430 --> 00:54:39.640
They might still bulge, because
the light would enter a slower

00:54:39.640 --> 00:54:42.845
middle, but they
wouldn't be spherical.

00:54:42.845 --> 00:54:44.220
Now, the fact that
the wavefronts

00:54:44.220 --> 00:54:45.400
would not be spherical.

00:54:45.400 --> 00:54:50.430
What it really implies is
that the focus is not perfect

00:54:50.430 --> 00:54:53.160
anymore.

00:54:53.160 --> 00:54:54.940
If these surfaces
of the wavefronts,

00:54:54.940 --> 00:54:57.420
they deviate from spheres.

00:54:57.420 --> 00:55:00.930
Then the rays would not
really all be at [? F, ?]

00:55:00.930 --> 00:55:04.240
but they would cross
at various places.

00:55:04.240 --> 00:55:08.220
And that is what you
call an aberrated image,

00:55:08.220 --> 00:55:09.920
or an aberrated wavefront.

00:55:09.920 --> 00:55:20.550
So the two are related, because
if, for example, the wavefront

00:55:20.550 --> 00:55:24.300
deviates from a sphere, then you
call it an aberrated wavefront.

00:55:24.300 --> 00:55:28.380
If the image deviates from
the ideal point image, where

00:55:28.380 --> 00:55:30.990
all the rays meet to
a sort of blurry image

00:55:30.990 --> 00:55:34.680
where the rays fail to meet,
then that's an aberrated image.

00:55:34.680 --> 00:55:36.840
So I will show some
examples of that

00:55:36.840 --> 00:55:41.290
later on, today, and also
later during the class.

00:55:41.290 --> 00:55:46.470
So there's a special
case when the--

00:55:46.470 --> 00:55:48.480
well, let me save that
special case for later.

00:55:51.030 --> 00:55:54.730
I will talk about
this in a little bit.

00:55:54.730 --> 00:55:58.410
What I would like to say next
is why is it so significant to--

00:55:58.410 --> 00:56:01.740
why do we try so hard to
create these point images?

00:56:08.100 --> 00:56:11.660
We're surrounded by
objects that are--

00:56:11.660 --> 00:56:14.870
actually, most of the
objects that we see around us

00:56:14.870 --> 00:56:17.400
are reflective.

00:56:17.400 --> 00:56:18.650
They are opaque.

00:56:18.650 --> 00:56:23.760
So light that is entered
in from a light source,

00:56:23.760 --> 00:56:26.640
for example, a light
bulb, or the sunlight when

00:56:26.640 --> 00:56:27.810
we're outdoors.

00:56:27.810 --> 00:56:31.270
What happens to the light
as it hits the objects that

00:56:31.270 --> 00:56:32.700
are surrounding us.

00:56:32.700 --> 00:56:34.350
It scatters.

00:56:34.350 --> 00:56:37.320
So scattering really
means that the light

00:56:37.320 --> 00:56:39.660
that is arriving from a source.

00:56:39.660 --> 00:56:43.800
Each point in the object, it
creates a highly divergent

00:56:43.800 --> 00:56:45.060
spherical wave.

00:56:45.060 --> 00:56:46.920
So basically, each
point in the object

00:56:46.920 --> 00:56:50.160
becomes a secondary
point source.

00:56:50.160 --> 00:56:51.600
This is part of a big--

00:56:51.600 --> 00:56:54.540
of another principle
in light propagation

00:56:54.540 --> 00:56:56.640
called the Huygen's principle.

00:56:56.640 --> 00:56:59.050
But we're not quite ready
to see that principle yet.

00:56:59.050 --> 00:57:02.610
It needs a little bit
more careful definition.

00:57:02.610 --> 00:57:06.000
So for now, one way to
justify in your mind

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:10.040
why this might happen is that
the objects surrounding us.

00:57:10.040 --> 00:57:12.210
They are composed of atoms.

00:57:12.210 --> 00:57:17.190
And each atom, when it
gets hit by the light beam.

00:57:17.190 --> 00:57:18.690
It will be set in motion.

00:57:18.690 --> 00:57:20.280
And you can imagine
the situation

00:57:20.280 --> 00:57:24.120
where the motion of the atom
will irradiate a new light

00:57:24.120 --> 00:57:24.900
beam.

00:57:24.900 --> 00:57:26.580
So these light beams
that are coming out

00:57:26.580 --> 00:57:33.380
of there of the atoms composing
the surfaces surrounding us.

00:57:33.380 --> 00:57:36.020
This is what we perceive as--

00:57:36.020 --> 00:57:40.047
I should say, what we
receive as scattered light.

00:57:40.047 --> 00:57:41.880
And it sounds a little
bit like hocus pocus,

00:57:41.880 --> 00:57:43.713
but it's actually not
very far from reality.

00:57:43.713 --> 00:57:45.870
You can justify
the argument I just

00:57:45.870 --> 00:57:50.300
made with some very
basic principles.

00:57:50.300 --> 00:57:51.883
So it is more or less correct.

00:57:51.883 --> 00:57:53.550
The bottom line is
that the illumination

00:57:53.550 --> 00:57:56.880
becomes these divergent
spherical wavefronts.

00:57:56.880 --> 00:57:58.980
Now, if you are sitting
here, and you're

00:57:58.980 --> 00:58:02.130
observing all the rays
coming from the object.

00:58:02.130 --> 00:58:05.610
You can imagine
that it's a mess.

00:58:05.610 --> 00:58:08.310
For example, here, you have
rays coming from this point,

00:58:08.310 --> 00:58:10.440
and from this point,
and from this point,

00:58:10.440 --> 00:58:13.230
from everywhere, everywhere
inside the object.

00:58:13.230 --> 00:58:15.240
You have rays arriving here.

00:58:15.240 --> 00:58:17.490
So it is very difficult to
understand what's going on.

00:58:17.490 --> 00:58:21.420
All of these rays, they create
kind of a very blurred image,

00:58:21.420 --> 00:58:25.450
very similar to what happens to
those of us who have glasses.

00:58:25.450 --> 00:58:28.500
When we take off our glasses,
everything appears blurry.

00:58:28.500 --> 00:58:31.380
Well, it is not as bad as it
would have been in this case.

00:58:31.380 --> 00:58:36.390
But the reason things are blurry
in our eyes is because when we

00:58:36.390 --> 00:58:40.330
take our glasses off, we
cannot form that effect--

00:58:40.330 --> 00:58:42.480
well, it's never
perfect, but we can not

00:58:42.480 --> 00:58:48.842
form good enough quality
images in our eye.

00:58:48.842 --> 00:58:51.300
So what we need in order to
design these kind of situations

00:58:51.300 --> 00:58:54.720
is an optical
system, or a sequence

00:58:54.720 --> 00:58:57.210
of optical elements
that will pick up

00:58:57.210 --> 00:59:00.450
these divergent
spherical wavefronts,

00:59:00.450 --> 00:59:03.870
and will convert
them into converging

00:59:03.870 --> 00:59:05.730
spherical wavefronts.

00:59:05.730 --> 00:59:08.130
And if we can somehow
create an optical system

00:59:08.130 --> 00:59:11.670
that will take each and every
one of these wavefronts.

00:59:11.670 --> 00:59:17.040
Now, we're talking, of course,
about an infinitely large

00:59:17.040 --> 00:59:22.920
number of point scatterers
that are generated here.

00:59:22.920 --> 00:59:25.530
But if you can somehow take
each and every one of them,

00:59:25.530 --> 00:59:31.290
and I can convert it into a
converging spherical wave, then

00:59:31.290 --> 00:59:34.840
when I put all these converging
spherical waves together,

00:59:34.840 --> 00:59:36.480
I will actually
get an image, which

00:59:36.480 --> 00:59:39.600
will be as close to
perfect as I could possibly

00:59:39.600 --> 00:59:41.820
want within the limits
of approximation

00:59:41.820 --> 00:59:45.240
of geometrical optics.

00:59:45.240 --> 00:59:47.280
Another way to express
it, which is really

00:59:47.280 --> 00:59:50.580
like a fancy mathematical term,
but it is quite appropriate

00:59:50.580 --> 00:59:55.130
here is the imaging
system creates a map.

00:59:55.130 --> 01:00:00.820
Creates a map from point
sources in the object space

01:00:00.820 --> 01:00:05.090
to point images in
the image space.

01:00:05.090 --> 01:00:07.970
And this map is, of
course, very desirable.

01:00:07.970 --> 01:00:12.860
Because if it fails, if I tried
to detect the image over here

01:00:12.860 --> 01:00:17.270
that is before the rays
have come to focus.

01:00:17.270 --> 01:00:20.840
Then the map
becomes ill-defined,

01:00:20.840 --> 01:00:24.820
because each point over
here is receiving arrays

01:00:24.820 --> 01:00:26.970
from multiple points
in the object.

01:00:26.970 --> 01:00:28.760
This is exactly
the same situation

01:00:28.760 --> 01:00:32.270
I was referring to before,
when we take off our glasses.

01:00:32.270 --> 01:00:35.360
Those of us unfortunate
enough to require glasses.

01:00:35.360 --> 01:00:39.350
For the rest of you who do not
need glasses in everyday life,

01:00:39.350 --> 01:00:41.630
you can, of course,
create that same situation

01:00:41.630 --> 01:00:45.350
by putting on a pair of
glasses that you can borrow

01:00:45.350 --> 01:00:46.940
from one of your colleagues.

01:00:46.940 --> 01:00:48.500
So in both cases,
you can add what

01:00:48.500 --> 01:00:50.360
we call the focus,
which basically

01:00:50.360 --> 01:00:54.680
means that the image is not just
imperfect, but it is blurry.

01:00:54.680 --> 01:00:58.290
It is very far from perfect.

01:00:58.290 --> 01:01:01.650
However, from what you
must have gathered already

01:01:01.650 --> 01:01:05.100
from the previous discussion,
this is a very difficult task.

01:01:05.100 --> 01:01:07.170
In fact, it is an
impossible task.

01:01:07.170 --> 01:01:12.660
Because you saw that even
in the case of a simple,

01:01:12.660 --> 01:01:17.440
ellipsoidal, or hyperboloidal
focusing element.

01:01:17.440 --> 01:01:22.830
You could see that the one to
one mapping works only on axis.

01:01:22.830 --> 01:01:27.320
If you tried to focus
simultaneously points off axis,

01:01:27.320 --> 01:01:31.220
well, then, of course,
it stops to work.

01:01:31.220 --> 01:01:34.390
It is very easy to convince
yourself in geometrical terms.

01:01:34.390 --> 01:01:36.170
Even then, there is
some special cases

01:01:36.170 --> 01:01:39.110
where you can have an entire
surface that is in focus.

01:01:39.110 --> 01:01:41.300
But we will talk
about this later.

01:01:43.910 --> 01:01:46.520
So this is actually--

01:01:46.520 --> 01:01:50.060
you could think of it as
a very unfortunate event.

01:01:50.060 --> 01:01:51.920
I think it as a fortunate
event, because it

01:01:51.920 --> 01:01:54.720
keeps people like me,
and Professor Sheppard,

01:01:54.720 --> 01:01:57.680
and a lot of colleagues,
it keeps us employed.

01:01:57.680 --> 01:02:00.080
Because this is the
whole reason people

01:02:00.080 --> 01:02:03.140
need optical systems is
they need people like us.

01:02:03.140 --> 01:02:06.890
So it is a very fortunate fact.

01:02:06.890 --> 01:02:11.930
But what I'm trying to say here
is that this job of perfect

01:02:11.930 --> 01:02:14.630
imaging cannot be done exactly.

01:02:14.630 --> 01:02:17.210
So therefore, the
science, or if you wish,

01:02:17.210 --> 01:02:19.890
the engineering of
designing optical systems

01:02:19.890 --> 01:02:23.150
is to arrive at the best
compromise within the cost,

01:02:23.150 --> 01:02:26.630
constraints, the elements
that you have available,

01:02:26.630 --> 01:02:30.607
the physics, of course, this
is definitely inviolable.

01:02:30.607 --> 01:02:31.940
You can violate a budget, right?

01:02:31.940 --> 01:02:33.830
You can run a
budget into the red,

01:02:33.830 --> 01:02:37.450
as Wall Street banks discovered
in the last six months.

01:02:37.450 --> 01:02:39.200
But you can certainly
not violate physics.

01:02:39.200 --> 01:02:41.540
Even bankers cannot
violate physics.

01:02:41.540 --> 01:02:44.600
So within all these constraints
imposed by physics, economics,

01:02:44.600 --> 01:02:47.270
and so on so forth, how can
you make an imaging system that

01:02:47.270 --> 01:02:51.150
does the best job possible?

01:02:51.150 --> 01:02:56.100
OK, so let's go back
to this question

01:02:56.100 --> 01:03:00.610
of how can we create good
enough quality images so that we

01:03:00.610 --> 01:03:02.920
can design imaging systems?

01:03:02.920 --> 01:03:05.630
So let's look at a slightly
different case, now.

01:03:05.630 --> 01:03:10.520
So far, we saw pairs of
images and sources, where

01:03:10.520 --> 01:03:12.020
one of the tools at infinity.

01:03:12.020 --> 01:03:14.930
So objects at infinity,
finite images.

01:03:17.560 --> 01:03:23.210
I mean, finite distant sources
and images at infinity.

01:03:23.210 --> 01:03:25.460
We start to deal with this
case, where we have a point

01:03:25.460 --> 01:03:27.750
object and a point image.

01:03:27.750 --> 01:03:30.350
So both are now at
finite distances.

01:03:30.350 --> 01:03:34.773
Based on what we saw so far,
and assuming that you're not

01:03:34.773 --> 01:03:35.690
looking at your notes.

01:03:35.690 --> 01:03:37.190
The answer is already
in your notes,

01:03:37.190 --> 01:03:39.560
if you reach that
page in the notes.

01:03:39.560 --> 01:03:42.720
But if you haven't seen that,
then your time to guess.

01:03:42.720 --> 01:03:45.780
What would be the ideal
imager for this case that

01:03:45.780 --> 01:03:51.780
would take a point object
and focus it perfectly

01:03:51.780 --> 01:03:55.140
into a point image on axis?

01:03:55.140 --> 01:03:56.960
Did we not answer
already based on--

01:04:04.990 --> 01:04:09.340
AUDIENCE: The concatenation
of two hyperbolic reflectors.

01:04:09.340 --> 01:04:11.020
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
That's right.

01:04:11.020 --> 01:04:13.587
So that is not necessarily
one way of doing it,

01:04:13.587 --> 01:04:15.170
but it's certainly
one way of doing it

01:04:15.170 --> 01:04:16.900
based on what we learn.

01:04:16.900 --> 01:04:20.200
If I put two refractive
surfaces like this,

01:04:20.200 --> 01:04:23.350
I can arrange the first
one to be a hyperbola.

01:04:23.350 --> 01:04:27.340
What it will do is
it will collimate.

01:04:27.340 --> 01:04:32.190
Yeah, it will collimate the
incident divergent wavefront.

01:04:32.190 --> 01:04:34.760
And then if I can arrange
for the second one

01:04:34.760 --> 01:04:40.000
to be also hyperbola,
then that will focus.

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:43.330
The plane wave that
was propagated here,

01:04:43.330 --> 01:04:46.880
it will focus into a
perfect point image.

01:04:46.880 --> 01:04:49.120
So this is now, again,
a perfect imager.

01:04:49.120 --> 01:04:51.730
But now, it works
for finite distances.

01:04:51.730 --> 01:04:54.640
One focal distance in
front of the hyperbola

01:04:54.640 --> 01:04:58.610
to one focal distance
after the hyperbola.

01:04:58.610 --> 01:05:03.860
And, well, just for
references, these

01:05:03.860 --> 01:05:06.050
are the two questions
of the hyperbola.

01:05:06.050 --> 01:05:08.090
I was a little bit
careful here to define

01:05:08.090 --> 01:05:10.775
the axis, and the
displacement, and so on,

01:05:10.775 --> 01:05:11.900
so that the question works.

01:05:11.900 --> 01:05:13.240
I don't want to belabor that.

01:05:13.240 --> 01:05:16.930
I let you go back and convince
yourself that it is correct,

01:05:16.930 --> 01:05:19.460
or convince yourself that is
not correct, in which case,

01:05:19.460 --> 01:05:22.140
please let me know so
that I can correct it.

01:05:22.140 --> 01:05:23.680
But I think I got it right.

01:05:23.680 --> 01:05:27.370
Anyway, so these are the two
equations of the hyperboloids.

01:05:27.370 --> 01:05:30.020
And this is what in
optics is very often

01:05:30.020 --> 01:05:32.880
referred to as an asphere.

01:05:32.880 --> 01:05:36.930
Now, this can be
slightly confusing.

01:05:36.930 --> 01:05:39.490
So I'm going to say
it a few times here,

01:05:39.490 --> 01:05:41.780
and then I'm going to ask
you to go back home, read it

01:05:41.780 --> 01:05:44.260
a few times, then print it out.

01:05:44.260 --> 01:05:46.760
Post it in front of
your bathroom mirror

01:05:46.760 --> 01:05:49.320
on top of your bed
and so on, whatever.

01:05:49.320 --> 01:05:52.740
So you can see it a few
times, and memorize it.

01:05:52.740 --> 01:05:57.230
OK, so this type of
element whose surface

01:05:57.230 --> 01:06:02.450
is optimized to give a
desired focus and behavior

01:06:02.450 --> 01:06:04.220
is called in asphere.

01:06:04.220 --> 01:06:06.200
Again, I have a
benefit being Greek.

01:06:06.200 --> 01:06:10.220
This A in front of the
sphere means not a sphere.

01:06:15.710 --> 01:06:17.190
Give an example
from everyday life.

01:06:17.190 --> 01:06:18.580
I can only think
technical terms,

01:06:18.580 --> 01:06:21.530
and isotropic, aplanatic.

01:06:21.530 --> 01:06:23.840
Give me an example of
from everyday life.

01:06:23.840 --> 01:06:24.655
AUDIENCE: Atypical?

01:06:24.655 --> 01:06:26.780
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Atypical, there you are, yeah.

01:06:26.780 --> 01:06:27.280
Thank you.

01:06:29.990 --> 01:06:32.800
OK, so it is atypical
as in asphere.

01:06:32.800 --> 01:06:36.250
So another term that
is very commonly used

01:06:36.250 --> 01:06:37.750
is in aspheric lens.

01:06:43.180 --> 01:06:47.800
Again, I want to emphasize
that this kind of a sphere.

01:06:47.800 --> 01:06:50.542
It works perfectly on axis.

01:06:50.542 --> 01:06:52.000
But as you can
imagine, if you were

01:06:52.000 --> 01:06:56.230
to move this point object
off axis, it would go off.

01:06:56.230 --> 01:07:00.440
It could create an image, but
it would be highly aberrated.

01:07:00.440 --> 01:07:04.865
It would be subject to, well,
definitely spherical and comma

01:07:04.865 --> 01:07:05.365
possibly.

01:07:08.438 --> 01:07:09.480
It's a complicated story.

01:07:14.743 --> 01:07:16.910
You can imagine that this
doesn't happen at the way.

01:07:16.910 --> 01:07:20.220
There's probably a range over
here for point sources at that

01:07:20.220 --> 01:07:24.110
near enough the axis that this
refractor would work actually

01:07:24.110 --> 01:07:25.280
quite well.

01:07:25.280 --> 01:07:27.230
So the question is can
I make such an element?

01:07:31.300 --> 01:07:33.060
To answer this question,
I should tell you

01:07:33.060 --> 01:07:36.690
a little bit about how optical
elements are usually made.

01:07:36.690 --> 01:07:39.480
So what people at
least used to do

01:07:39.480 --> 01:07:42.630
in the old days of
expensive optical elements,

01:07:42.630 --> 01:07:44.130
is they would take
a piece of glass.

01:07:44.130 --> 01:07:47.160
They would mount it
on a rotary stage.

01:07:47.160 --> 01:07:51.150
Then they would bring a
diamond tip near the glass.

01:07:51.150 --> 01:07:53.700
And they would start
rotating the glass.

01:07:53.700 --> 01:07:58.785
And they would rotate basically
not at all at the center,

01:07:58.785 --> 01:08:01.860
and they would let the
diamond touch the glass longer

01:08:01.860 --> 01:08:06.345
and longer as they went away
from the tip of the glass.

01:08:06.345 --> 01:08:07.720
The result of that
is, of course,

01:08:07.720 --> 01:08:09.630
that you create a
spherical surface

01:08:09.630 --> 01:08:13.050
if you move the diamond
at a fixed velocity.

01:08:13.050 --> 01:08:15.750
So a fixed velocity
was very easy.

01:08:15.750 --> 01:08:17.430
Because all you
needed is a model that

01:08:17.430 --> 01:08:20.430
moves a diamond tip linearly.

01:08:20.430 --> 01:08:22.229
That's pretty easy to do.

01:08:22.229 --> 01:08:25.770
To make a hyperbola, you have
to plant the path of the diamond

01:08:25.770 --> 01:08:31.970
tip in a way that results in
this nonuniform curvature.

01:08:31.970 --> 01:08:35.189
So this used to be thought
as a very difficult task.

01:08:35.189 --> 01:08:35.689
Come on in.

01:08:35.689 --> 01:08:36.410
Someone's outside.

01:08:36.410 --> 01:08:36.910
Come on in.

01:08:36.910 --> 01:08:39.404
Don't be shy.

01:08:39.404 --> 01:08:40.279
She changed her mind.

01:08:45.710 --> 01:08:50.359
But in the last 20
years or so, the field

01:08:50.359 --> 01:08:53.038
of mechatronics that many of
you are familiar with then

01:08:53.038 --> 01:08:53.830
had advanced a lot.

01:08:53.830 --> 01:08:58.310
So people who are able to
design diamond tools that

01:08:58.310 --> 01:09:01.939
could very carefully plan
the path of the diamond tip,

01:09:01.939 --> 01:09:05.580
and actually create aspheric
elements, such as this one.

01:09:05.580 --> 01:09:07.140
But it still remains
very expensive.

01:09:07.140 --> 01:09:10.408
So it could be an order of
magnitude difference in price.

01:09:10.408 --> 01:09:12.200
If you need to compare
a spherical element,

01:09:12.200 --> 01:09:14.040
compare it to an asphere.

01:09:14.040 --> 01:09:14.540
Another

01:09:14.540 --> 01:09:18.140
Major invention that helped this
business is injection molding.

01:09:18.140 --> 01:09:20.330
Instead of actually
making the optical element

01:09:20.330 --> 01:09:22.160
itself, what people
do nowadays is

01:09:22.160 --> 01:09:24.859
they can make a very
expensive negative.

01:09:24.859 --> 01:09:28.069
And then they inject
plastic into the negative.

01:09:28.069 --> 01:09:30.439
They solidify the plastic,
and then they take it out.

01:09:30.439 --> 01:09:33.319
And they can get any
arbitrary surface they want.

01:09:33.319 --> 01:09:36.529
That's an OK way to make
a spheric optical element.

01:09:36.529 --> 01:09:39.605
Nevertheless, spherical
elements remain very popular.

01:09:39.605 --> 01:09:42.470
And there's a number of reasons
for these, [INAUDIBLE] spheres.

01:09:42.470 --> 01:09:45.500
They can work very
well on axis, but they

01:09:45.500 --> 01:09:47.870
can have other problems
that are perhaps

01:09:47.870 --> 01:09:51.500
much more severe when they
go off axis, which is not a--

01:09:51.500 --> 01:09:53.479
it is not a shoe
in, so to speak,

01:09:53.479 --> 01:09:57.630
to use aspheric
optical elements.

01:09:57.630 --> 01:10:02.140
So for that reason, we'll
spend quite a bit of time,

01:10:02.140 --> 01:10:06.190
and also, I guess,
because of tradition

01:10:06.190 --> 01:10:09.310
to analyze what happens
to light as it goes

01:10:09.310 --> 01:10:12.947
through spherical surfaces.

01:10:12.947 --> 01:10:14.280
So spherical surface, of course.

01:10:14.280 --> 01:10:17.470
If you replace the hyperbolas
here with a sphere.

01:10:17.470 --> 01:10:20.800
Let's say I take a sphere.

01:10:20.800 --> 01:10:23.050
I need to say this very
clearly, because the terms can

01:10:23.050 --> 01:10:24.370
become confusing.

01:10:24.370 --> 01:10:28.960
If I replace the asphere
with a perfect sphere,

01:10:28.960 --> 01:10:30.292
that is, with a ball.

01:10:30.292 --> 01:10:32.500
Then, of course, as you can
imagine, what will happen

01:10:32.500 --> 01:10:35.290
is the wavefront,
even inside the sphere

01:10:35.290 --> 01:10:37.100
will not be planar anymore.

01:10:37.100 --> 01:10:39.370
You can convince yourself
if you think about it

01:10:39.370 --> 01:10:42.940
that because this sphere
actually bends faster

01:10:42.940 --> 01:10:46.690
than the hyperbola, the arrays
that are away from the axes.

01:10:46.690 --> 01:10:47.980
They will bend more.

01:10:47.980 --> 01:10:52.323
So you get a slightly focusing
in effect inside the sphere.

01:10:52.323 --> 01:10:53.990
Because, of course,
not a perfect focus.

01:10:53.990 --> 01:10:56.312
It is itself very
high aberrated.

01:10:56.312 --> 01:10:57.770
And by the time
they come out, they

01:10:57.770 --> 01:10:59.150
become aberrated even more.

01:10:59.150 --> 01:11:03.530
So you get a very poor
quality focus in general.

01:11:03.530 --> 01:11:06.010
There is a special case
where this might not happen,

01:11:06.010 --> 01:11:07.790
but I will skip that for now.

01:11:07.790 --> 01:11:10.020
So in general, you get
an aberrated image.

01:11:10.020 --> 01:11:12.620
So this is what they meant
before by aberration.

01:11:12.620 --> 01:11:15.230
You see that the rays,
they form a blur here.

01:11:15.230 --> 01:11:17.750
They fail to meet at
the perfect focus,

01:11:17.750 --> 01:11:20.360
as it would have been required
by the perfect optical system.

01:11:23.470 --> 01:11:27.460
And this particular
type of aberration

01:11:27.460 --> 01:11:32.020
that occurs when you
use a spherical surface

01:11:32.020 --> 01:11:35.650
or axis in this system is
called spherical aberration.

01:11:35.650 --> 01:11:37.660
Someone asked earlier
about spherical.

01:11:37.660 --> 01:11:38.530
This is spherical.

01:11:38.530 --> 01:11:40.728
AUDIENCE: I've got a question.

01:11:40.728 --> 01:11:41.770
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yes.

01:11:41.770 --> 01:11:42.985
AUDIENCE: How do you pick z2?

01:11:45.800 --> 01:11:48.760
Like where do you
choose to pick z2?

01:11:48.760 --> 01:11:51.730
Is it at the focus
of the closest rays,

01:11:51.730 --> 01:11:54.070
or the furthest rays?

01:11:54.070 --> 01:11:56.153
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: This
came from the hyperbola.

01:12:14.130 --> 01:12:16.350
z1, z2, they come
from the hyperbola.

01:12:16.350 --> 01:12:20.960
Depending on the curvature
over here, define z1 and z2.

01:12:24.520 --> 01:12:27.000
And then I selected
the sphere to match

01:12:27.000 --> 01:12:30.200
the curvature of the
hyperbola near to the axis.

01:12:30.200 --> 01:12:33.090
So if you look at
the animation again.

01:12:33.090 --> 01:12:36.920
Near the axis, you will see that
they actually perfectly match.

01:12:36.920 --> 01:12:39.900
But then, of course,
the sphere carves faster

01:12:39.900 --> 01:12:43.165
than the hyperbola.

01:12:43.165 --> 01:12:44.540
AUDIENCE: I think
the question is

01:12:44.540 --> 01:12:48.170
in the spherically aberrated
case where you can not

01:12:48.170 --> 01:12:53.698
find all the points meeting,
how can you define the z2?

01:12:53.698 --> 01:12:55.990
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: OK,
that's a really good question.

01:12:55.990 --> 01:12:58.670
So the way you
defined z2 is you look

01:12:58.670 --> 01:13:02.570
at the two rays that are really,
really close to the axis.

01:13:02.570 --> 01:13:04.380
For those two rays
that are propagating

01:13:04.380 --> 01:13:08.457
at the very small angle,
then the same z2 applies.

01:13:08.457 --> 01:13:10.040
Then, of course, the
rest of the rays.

01:13:10.040 --> 01:13:15.280
They go off very
far from that point.

01:13:15.280 --> 01:13:18.180
But anyways, z2 here is exactly
the same as it was before.

01:13:22.290 --> 01:13:23.540
Did that answer your question?

01:13:27.627 --> 01:13:28.210
AUDIENCE: Yes.

01:13:28.210 --> 01:13:33.970
Long

01:13:33.970 --> 01:13:35.950
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Now, if you go off axis,

01:13:35.950 --> 01:13:38.405
then other types of
aberrations kick in.

01:13:38.405 --> 01:13:39.780
So we're not
mentioning them now.

01:13:39.780 --> 01:13:41.980
We'll come back to
this topic later,

01:13:41.980 --> 01:13:45.420
and we find them in more detail.

01:13:45.420 --> 01:13:48.590
But for now, keep this
in mind, that if you

01:13:48.590 --> 01:13:54.110
use a sphere on axis.

01:13:54.110 --> 01:13:55.390
Let me repeat.

01:13:55.390 --> 01:14:01.000
If you use a sphere to
focus a point source on axis

01:14:01.000 --> 01:14:04.460
into a point image, also an
axis at the finite distance,

01:14:04.460 --> 01:14:06.370
then you get spherical
aberration in general.

01:14:13.560 --> 01:14:19.670
Well, that is true, but
if you put it over here.

01:14:19.670 --> 01:14:21.990
Just move the axis, yes.

01:14:21.990 --> 01:14:23.730
Well, yeah.

01:14:23.730 --> 01:14:26.310
OK.

01:14:26.310 --> 01:14:28.260
Yeah, thank you.

01:14:28.260 --> 01:14:30.880
Let me define what I
mean by the axis here.

01:14:30.880 --> 01:14:35.550
So typically, film and
camera is the elements

01:14:35.550 --> 01:14:40.330
that we use in order
to capture images flat.

01:14:40.330 --> 01:14:46.800
So if I put here
either my camera lens.

01:14:46.800 --> 01:14:49.480
I should say the tip of
the camera, the camera

01:14:49.480 --> 01:14:54.120
dial, or a film.

01:14:54.120 --> 01:14:57.210
That defines an axis that is
perpendicular to the film.

01:14:57.210 --> 01:14:59.700
So Colin is correct, that
if I take a point here,

01:14:59.700 --> 01:15:03.240
and then move it sort of
radially through the sphere.

01:15:03.240 --> 01:15:06.660
It will form a perfect
image over here.

01:15:06.660 --> 01:15:10.420
The fact that I try to detect
the image not at this point,

01:15:10.420 --> 01:15:13.740
but on the plane, means that I
will be subject to aberrations.

01:15:13.740 --> 01:15:17.930
This is the proper
definition of aberration.

01:15:17.930 --> 01:15:20.310
And, of course, even
the on axis point

01:15:20.310 --> 01:15:25.170
will have spherical aberration,
as I mentioned earlier.

01:15:28.535 --> 01:15:29.660
Did I answer that question?

01:15:35.090 --> 01:15:38.610
OK, so let's see how we
deal with the refraction

01:15:38.610 --> 01:15:39.300
from a sphere.

01:15:41.700 --> 01:15:43.200
So [INAUDIBLE],, as
you can imagine,

01:15:43.200 --> 01:15:45.990
is a quite complicated
problem because here

01:15:45.990 --> 01:15:51.150
is a ray that is arriving from
some point source on axis.

01:15:51.150 --> 01:15:52.770
It hits the sphere.

01:15:52.770 --> 01:15:55.530
And then my job is to find
which direction this ray

01:15:55.530 --> 01:15:58.670
will be refracted
inside the sphere.

01:15:58.670 --> 01:16:01.010
So now, again, I can
use one of the tools

01:16:01.010 --> 01:16:02.300
that we have in our arsenal.

01:16:02.300 --> 01:16:06.230
I can use Fermat's principle,
or I can use Snell's law.

01:16:06.230 --> 01:16:08.155
The two are, of
course, identical.

01:16:08.155 --> 01:16:09.780
The fact of the matter
is in this case,

01:16:09.780 --> 01:16:13.160
it would be quite
complicated to do.

01:16:13.160 --> 01:16:15.200
So we'll do simplification.

01:16:15.200 --> 01:16:17.840
First of all, let's
define some notation here.

01:16:17.840 --> 01:16:21.340
I will denote as x the
distance of the ray

01:16:21.340 --> 01:16:23.550
intersects the sphere.

01:16:23.550 --> 01:16:29.690
I will define as
alpha left the angle

01:16:29.690 --> 01:16:31.730
that the ray makes
with the optical axis

01:16:31.730 --> 01:16:34.860
to the left of the interface.

01:16:34.860 --> 01:16:36.910
This is the interface.

01:16:36.910 --> 01:16:38.900
And then alpha
right is the angle

01:16:38.900 --> 01:16:41.820
that the ray makes with
respect to the horizontal,

01:16:41.820 --> 01:16:47.260
the optical axis the right
hand side of the interface.

01:16:47.260 --> 01:16:48.730
OK, that's my notation.

01:16:48.730 --> 01:16:51.710
And now for generality,
I do not assume

01:16:51.710 --> 01:16:53.440
that this is air
anymore, I just assume

01:16:53.440 --> 01:16:55.550
that I have two dielectrics.

01:16:55.550 --> 01:16:58.490
One has index n sub
left, and the other

01:16:58.490 --> 01:17:00.850
has index n sub right.

01:17:00.850 --> 01:17:03.350
It's a little bit cumbersome
to carry left and right around,

01:17:03.350 --> 01:17:06.650
but it is convenient because we
will leave that for a mnemonic

01:17:06.650 --> 01:17:08.947
later on.

01:17:08.947 --> 01:17:10.280
So how do we solve this problem?

01:17:10.280 --> 01:17:13.680
Well, the way I elected to
solve it is a little bit easier,

01:17:13.680 --> 01:17:15.460
it turns out.

01:17:15.460 --> 01:17:17.590
So for the first
time, today I will not

01:17:17.590 --> 01:17:18.940
use Fermat's principle.

01:17:18.940 --> 01:17:20.680
I will use Snell's law.

01:17:20.680 --> 01:17:22.147
And, of course,
Snell's law follows

01:17:22.147 --> 01:17:23.980
from Fermat's principle,
so I haven't really

01:17:23.980 --> 01:17:25.060
changed anything.

01:17:25.060 --> 01:17:29.020
It's just more convenient
to do the math this way.

01:17:29.020 --> 01:17:32.320
So to apply Snell's law,
I have to figure out

01:17:32.320 --> 01:17:36.070
which way is the
perpendicular to the interface

01:17:36.070 --> 01:17:40.840
at the cross section of the
ray with a spherical surface.

01:17:40.840 --> 01:17:44.170
And, of course, if I have
a sphere conveniently,

01:17:44.170 --> 01:17:48.510
the normal to the sphere
goes through the center.

01:17:48.510 --> 01:17:50.730
So here is the
normal to the sphere.

01:17:50.730 --> 01:17:54.480
It goes to the center, and
some additional rotation.

01:17:54.480 --> 01:17:58.650
I will denote as R, the
radius of the sphere.

01:17:58.650 --> 01:18:04.710
And phi, I will denote the angle
that this particular normal,

01:18:04.710 --> 01:18:07.920
this particular radius
makes with, again,

01:18:07.920 --> 01:18:09.840
with a horizontal axis.

01:18:13.220 --> 01:18:16.520
I think this is all the
notation that I needed.

01:18:16.520 --> 01:18:18.150
Actually, I'm not done yet.

01:18:18.150 --> 01:18:20.740
So I also to apply Snell's law.

01:18:20.740 --> 01:18:23.660
So to apply Snell's law, I
have to look at the angles that

01:18:23.660 --> 01:18:25.370
enter Snell's law.

01:18:25.370 --> 01:18:30.710
So if you recall, apply
Snell relative to the normal

01:18:30.710 --> 01:18:32.150
to the interface.

01:18:32.150 --> 01:18:34.370
So here's the normal,
here is the ray.

01:18:34.370 --> 01:18:36.950
Therefore, this
angle is theta that

01:18:36.950 --> 01:18:40.820
will go on the left-hand
side of Snell's law.

01:18:40.820 --> 01:18:44.360
And the corresponding
is theta sub right

01:18:44.360 --> 01:18:47.990
that will go to the right-hand
side of Snell's law.

01:18:47.990 --> 01:18:52.880
So speaking of which,
here is Snell's law--

01:18:52.880 --> 01:18:56.690
n left times the sine of the
angle on the left-hand side

01:18:56.690 --> 01:18:59.870
will equal n to the right
times the sine of the angle

01:18:59.870 --> 01:19:02.390
on the right-hand side.

01:19:02.390 --> 01:19:05.890
And now I have to do a
little a bit of geometry.

01:19:05.890 --> 01:19:08.650
So these angles, they
are not known to me yet.

01:19:08.650 --> 01:19:12.160
But I can observe
that alpha left

01:19:12.160 --> 01:19:15.160
is the same as the angle
from the horizontal

01:19:15.160 --> 01:19:17.270
to the ray over here.

01:19:17.270 --> 01:19:21.880
And the angle from the
horizontal to the radius

01:19:21.880 --> 01:19:23.780
equals 5.

01:19:23.780 --> 01:19:27.730
So this means that I have
this property over here--

01:19:27.730 --> 01:19:30.830
theta left equals
alpha left plus 5

01:19:30.830 --> 01:19:34.370
in the corresponding equation
for the right-hand side.

01:19:34.370 --> 01:19:41.970
And I can also substitute
these two relationships

01:19:41.970 --> 01:19:43.525
into Snell's law.

01:19:43.525 --> 01:19:45.630
I can apply a little
bit of trigonometry

01:19:45.630 --> 01:19:48.540
in order to break
the sign of the sum

01:19:48.540 --> 01:19:50.910
into this rather
complicated-looking expression

01:19:50.910 --> 01:19:51.917
over here.

01:19:51.917 --> 01:19:53.250
So I haven't made much progress.

01:19:53.250 --> 01:19:55.650
So all I managed to do is
write a complicated set

01:19:55.650 --> 01:19:59.000
of trigonometric relationships.

01:19:59.000 --> 01:20:01.820
In fact, if I were to
do a numerical solution

01:20:01.820 --> 01:20:05.690
to this problem, I would
just stop here and feed it

01:20:05.690 --> 01:20:07.640
into a computer and solve.

01:20:07.640 --> 01:20:09.890
But I don't want to do that
quite yet, because there's

01:20:09.890 --> 01:20:11.840
quite a bit of
intuition to be derived

01:20:11.840 --> 01:20:17.315
before we go blindly into a
computer and plug the numerics.

01:20:17.315 --> 01:20:19.190
So of course, the thing
that we do in physics

01:20:19.190 --> 01:20:22.460
when we try to derive intuition
from a very complicated formula

01:20:22.460 --> 01:20:25.330
like this one is we
make approximations.

01:20:25.330 --> 01:20:27.500
And the reasonable
approximation to make here

01:20:27.500 --> 01:20:32.320
is that the rays that are
arriving to the element

01:20:32.320 --> 01:20:36.200
are limited in a relatively
small angular range.

01:20:36.200 --> 01:20:38.480
This turns out to be a
very practical assumption,

01:20:38.480 --> 01:20:42.110
because it is a very common
situation in optics to have

01:20:42.110 --> 01:20:49.050
this small angle approximation.

01:20:49.050 --> 01:20:51.830
And it turns out that even when
the small angle approximation

01:20:51.830 --> 01:20:53.870
is not exactly
right, you can still

01:20:53.870 --> 01:20:57.080
do a first pass of the
design of an optical system

01:20:57.080 --> 01:20:58.310
with this approximation.

01:20:58.310 --> 01:21:00.020
And then you can
improve it by doing

01:21:00.020 --> 01:21:02.562
sort of more complicated
numerical analysis.

01:21:02.562 --> 01:21:04.520
So it's a very good place
to start the analysis

01:21:04.520 --> 01:21:06.210
of an optical system.

01:21:06.210 --> 01:21:09.320
So the key assumption here is
that alpha sub left, this one,

01:21:09.320 --> 01:21:10.850
is very small.

01:21:10.850 --> 01:21:12.310
If that is true--

01:21:12.310 --> 01:21:14.130
and also, I need
one more assumption,

01:21:14.130 --> 01:21:16.850
which is that this
distance over here,

01:21:16.850 --> 01:21:20.990
the distance that a ray meets
the spherical interface,

01:21:20.990 --> 01:21:24.080
is much smaller than the
radius of the sphere.

01:21:24.080 --> 01:21:27.350
In other words, the
sphere is not very small,

01:21:27.350 --> 01:21:30.210
but it is a relatively
small curvature.

01:21:30.210 --> 01:21:30.710
All right?

01:21:30.710 --> 01:21:34.640
It has a relatively
large radius of curvature

01:21:34.640 --> 01:21:38.170
or, equivalently,
a small curvature.

01:21:38.170 --> 01:21:39.740
So the first
answers are correct.

01:21:39.740 --> 01:21:42.915
It is also reasonable to
assume that alpha right, so

01:21:42.915 --> 01:21:44.290
the right-hand
side of interface,

01:21:44.290 --> 01:21:46.380
is also very small angle.

01:21:46.380 --> 01:21:49.660
And if I make the
set of assumptions,

01:21:49.660 --> 01:21:53.660
the entire set is called
the paraxial approximation.

01:21:53.660 --> 01:21:57.710
So "paraxial" really means
that everything is confined

01:21:57.710 --> 01:22:02.480
to being near the optical axis.

01:22:02.480 --> 01:22:03.480
Very well.

01:22:03.480 --> 01:22:06.270
So if we do this approximation
now, a lot of this

01:22:06.270 --> 01:22:09.740
gets simplified because
of this Taylor series.

01:22:09.740 --> 01:22:13.970
The sine of the angle of a small
angles equals the angle itself.

01:22:13.970 --> 01:22:16.990
The cosine of a
small angle equals 1.

01:22:16.990 --> 01:22:21.998
And also, the sine of
this angle 5 is equal x/r.

01:22:21.998 --> 01:22:23.290
I don't have to touch that one.

01:22:23.290 --> 01:22:25.330
This one is actually exact.

01:22:25.330 --> 01:22:29.320
But I can also neglect the
cosine of pi, because--

01:22:29.320 --> 01:22:31.090
well, because,
again, we are making

01:22:31.090 --> 01:22:33.310
the paraxial approximation.

01:22:33.310 --> 01:22:35.750
So if I do that, and I do a
little bit of rearrangement

01:22:35.750 --> 01:22:38.240
here, I arrive at
this explanation

01:22:38.240 --> 01:22:41.540
that says that the
index of the right,

01:22:41.540 --> 01:22:45.350
the index to the right
time the angle to the right

01:22:45.350 --> 01:22:48.740
equals the index to the
left times the angle

01:22:48.740 --> 01:22:53.460
to the left times this
expression over here.

01:22:53.460 --> 01:22:54.960
You might wonder a
number of things.

01:22:54.960 --> 01:22:57.590
For example, why did I
leave the index here?

01:22:57.590 --> 01:22:58.910
I'm looking for alpha right.

01:22:58.910 --> 01:23:02.570
So why don't I just divide
along and get done with it?

01:23:02.570 --> 01:23:03.350
There is a reason.

01:23:03.350 --> 01:23:05.570
And it will become
apparent in the moment.

01:23:05.570 --> 01:23:07.100
But for now, I'm
almost done, right?

01:23:07.100 --> 01:23:09.340
I have managed to
do what I wanted.

01:23:09.340 --> 01:23:12.110
I have a pretty
closed-form expression

01:23:12.110 --> 01:23:16.980
for the angle of refraction
inside the sphere.

01:23:16.980 --> 01:23:20.760
Now I'm going to do
something really strange.

01:23:20.760 --> 01:23:22.690
I will derive a
similar expression

01:23:22.690 --> 01:23:25.493
for light propagating
in uniform space.

01:23:25.493 --> 01:23:27.160
Now, this sounds
totally useless, right?

01:23:27.160 --> 01:23:28.570
But let me do it anyway.

01:23:28.570 --> 01:23:30.490
And bear with me for a while.

01:23:30.490 --> 01:23:34.670
I have a ray which is
propagating in free space.

01:23:34.670 --> 01:23:38.810
For reasons of notation, I will
define two refractive indices

01:23:38.810 --> 01:23:40.070
that are equal.

01:23:40.070 --> 01:23:42.050
One is n left, one is n right.

01:23:42.050 --> 01:23:45.770
But they're both equal to the
same index of refraction n.

01:23:45.770 --> 01:23:50.110
And what I'm interested to do
is I'm interested in relating

01:23:50.110 --> 01:23:55.430
the angle of the ray on the
left-hand side with respect

01:23:55.430 --> 01:23:58.880
to this reference plane
over here and the elevation

01:23:58.880 --> 01:24:02.450
of the ray with respect to
the same plane with the same

01:24:02.450 --> 01:24:05.770
quantities at the
second reference plane--

01:24:05.770 --> 01:24:09.114
the elevation and the angle
of the right-hand side.

01:24:09.114 --> 01:24:11.090
[? There ?] are other
trivial problem,

01:24:11.090 --> 01:24:15.500
because, for example, Fermat
says that in free space,

01:24:15.500 --> 01:24:18.380
the ray must propagate
at a straight line.

01:24:18.380 --> 01:24:20.960
So therefore, I can immediately
derive that alpha left

01:24:20.960 --> 01:24:22.770
equals alpha right.

01:24:22.770 --> 01:24:24.110
Not very surprising, right?

01:24:24.110 --> 01:24:26.210
I'm stating the
obvious here, and I'm

01:24:26.210 --> 01:24:27.450
making a big deal out of it.

01:24:27.450 --> 01:24:30.040
But nevertheless, let
me write it like this.

01:24:30.040 --> 01:24:31.790
Since the indices are
the same, I can also

01:24:31.790 --> 01:24:34.500
multiply by those indices.

01:24:34.500 --> 01:24:38.620
And what about the elevations?

01:24:38.620 --> 01:24:41.180
Well, the elevations
satisfy a simple equation

01:24:41.180 --> 01:24:46.820
relating the tangent of the
angle of propagation multiplied

01:24:46.820 --> 01:24:49.520
by the propagation distance d.

01:24:49.520 --> 01:24:52.250
So the elevation to the
right equals the elevation

01:24:52.250 --> 01:24:55.520
to the left times this--

01:24:55.520 --> 01:24:57.540
time this quantity.

01:24:57.540 --> 01:25:00.547
And then in the spirit of the
paraxial approximation again,

01:25:00.547 --> 01:25:02.630
I'm going to drop the
tangent, because the tangent

01:25:02.630 --> 01:25:05.330
of a small angle equals
the angle itself.

01:25:05.330 --> 01:25:10.340
And I arrive at a
set of equations,

01:25:10.340 --> 01:25:14.240
x right equals x left
plus d times alpha left.

01:25:14.240 --> 01:25:16.670
And this equation
that I got before.

01:25:16.670 --> 01:25:18.290
So now let me put
the two together.

01:25:18.290 --> 01:25:21.360
Let me put the free space
propagation that I just

01:25:21.360 --> 01:25:25.430
derived, and relationship
between the ray elevation

01:25:25.430 --> 01:25:29.060
and the ray angle to the
left and to the right

01:25:29.060 --> 01:25:34.510
of a uniform space
of distance d,

01:25:34.510 --> 01:25:37.810
and the equation that
I just derived earlier

01:25:37.810 --> 01:25:44.610
for the refraction of a ray
from a spherical surface,

01:25:44.610 --> 01:25:50.480
spherical refractive
surface, of radius r.

01:25:50.480 --> 01:25:51.250
OK.

01:25:51.250 --> 01:25:54.160
So these are the two sets
of equations that we got.

01:25:54.160 --> 01:25:58.780
This is the set of equations
that I got immediately before.

01:25:58.780 --> 01:26:02.230
And this is the set of equations
that I saw that I got earlier

01:26:02.230 --> 01:26:06.630
when I solved the
refraction problem

01:26:06.630 --> 01:26:08.488
at the spherical interface.

01:26:08.488 --> 01:26:10.530
And again, I want to
emphasize that both of these

01:26:10.530 --> 01:26:12.750
are correct in the
paraxial approximation.

01:26:12.750 --> 01:26:14.850
These are not exact expressions.

01:26:14.850 --> 01:26:16.650
The equal sign is a
bit of an ambiguous

01:26:16.650 --> 01:26:18.420
here, because I've
sort of assumed

01:26:18.420 --> 01:26:20.458
that the paraxial
approximation is correct.

01:26:20.458 --> 01:26:22.250
So we're going on with
this assumption now.

01:26:22.250 --> 01:26:25.650
That's why I'm
putting equal signs.

01:26:25.650 --> 01:26:26.440
OK.

01:26:26.440 --> 01:26:28.180
And I added one
more equation that I

01:26:28.180 --> 01:26:31.840
didn't write before that
says that x to the left

01:26:31.840 --> 01:26:33.017
equals x to the right.

01:26:33.017 --> 01:26:34.850
In this case-- and this
is a trivial thing--

01:26:34.850 --> 01:26:37.610
it says that the
ray is continuous.

01:26:37.610 --> 01:26:41.200
It arrives at the interface
at the center point

01:26:41.200 --> 01:26:43.165
and leaves from the same point.

01:26:43.165 --> 01:26:44.290
And that's kind of obvious.

01:26:44.290 --> 01:26:45.850
The ray should not jump.

01:26:45.850 --> 01:26:47.980
So what is remarkable
about these equations

01:26:47.980 --> 01:26:51.670
is that they're
both fully there,

01:26:51.670 --> 01:26:53.770
and the relations--
and the quantities

01:26:53.770 --> 01:26:56.050
that they're linear
with respect to

01:26:56.050 --> 01:26:59.020
are these two
elements, the elevation

01:26:59.020 --> 01:27:02.580
and the angle of the ray.

01:27:02.580 --> 01:27:04.970
So you can think of them as
kind of transport equations.

01:27:04.970 --> 01:27:10.900
They allow you to
transport a ray from two

01:27:10.900 --> 01:27:13.100
very basic optical elements.

01:27:13.100 --> 01:27:15.340
One is free space propagation.

01:27:15.340 --> 01:27:18.610
It allows you to transport
a ray through uniform space.

01:27:18.610 --> 01:27:21.370
And the other is a
refractive interface.

01:27:21.370 --> 01:27:25.090
Again, it allows you
to transport the ray

01:27:25.090 --> 01:27:28.870
from the left to the right
of a refractive interface.

01:27:28.870 --> 01:27:33.400
And because they're linear,
we can also write them

01:27:33.400 --> 01:27:35.810
in matrix form as follows.

01:27:35.810 --> 01:27:37.090
This is not new.

01:27:37.090 --> 01:27:39.700
I just took these
equations and rewrote them.

01:27:39.700 --> 01:27:43.780
And I rewrote them in
a slightly funny way.

01:27:43.780 --> 01:27:49.240
I kept the index of
refraction times the angle.

01:27:49.240 --> 01:27:52.720
Can anybody-- now that
we see it in this form--

01:27:52.720 --> 01:27:54.220
I will go to the
matrix in a moment.

01:27:54.220 --> 01:27:55.762
But now that you
see it in this form,

01:27:55.762 --> 01:27:58.600
can anybody guess why did I
go through all this trouble

01:27:58.600 --> 01:28:01.870
to keep the index of
refraction in this expression?

01:28:01.870 --> 01:28:04.360
Why don't I just write
the angle by itself?

01:28:14.860 --> 01:28:16.990
Is there a case, a
situation that we've

01:28:16.990 --> 01:28:21.420
seen, where this quantity may
be conserved, for example?

01:28:35.090 --> 01:28:37.860
