dispersion thing again.

01:28:37.860 --> 01:28:41.460
Or where it depends-- where you
have different n's, I suppose,

01:28:41.460 --> 01:28:45.750
and therefore different angles
depending on your wavelengths.

01:28:45.750 --> 01:28:47.500
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yeah.

01:28:47.500 --> 01:28:49.580
Even simpler, actually.

01:28:49.580 --> 01:28:53.060
If you are think
of Snell's law--

01:28:53.060 --> 01:28:55.380
yeah, you're on the
right track there.

01:28:55.380 --> 01:29:17.030
If you think of Snell's
law, Snell's law

01:29:17.030 --> 01:29:23.940
says that n left sine
alpha left equals

01:29:23.940 --> 01:29:30.240
n right sine alpha right.

01:29:30.240 --> 01:29:32.450
And of course, in the
paraxial approximation

01:29:32.450 --> 01:29:34.470
I drop the sinusoids.

01:29:34.470 --> 01:29:37.770
So therefore, I arrive
to the conclusion

01:29:37.770 --> 01:29:41.310
that this quantity at the
first element of this vector

01:29:41.310 --> 01:29:44.780
is actually conserved.

01:29:44.780 --> 01:29:48.300
And [INAUDIBLE] of
course, you can go over it

01:29:48.300 --> 01:29:49.880
yourselves and
convince yourselves

01:29:49.880 --> 01:29:51.510
that the equation is correct.

01:29:51.510 --> 01:29:53.510
This is basically just
taking the same equation.

01:29:56.100 --> 01:30:04.660
And these matrices, we'll
use them in the next lecture

01:30:04.660 --> 01:30:05.950
in order to do ray tracing.

01:30:05.950 --> 01:30:08.620
So basically, an optical
element can always

01:30:08.620 --> 01:30:12.610
be decomposed in a sequence
of refractive interfaces

01:30:12.610 --> 01:30:16.420
and free space or uniform
space propagation.

01:30:16.420 --> 01:30:18.820
So the reason the
matrices are convenient--

01:30:18.820 --> 01:30:20.740
sort of jumping
ahead a little bit--

01:30:20.740 --> 01:30:25.090
is because if you have a
cascade of optical elements,

01:30:25.090 --> 01:30:28.660
then you can ray trace simply
by multiplying these matrices.

01:30:28.660 --> 01:30:32.290
I will do that in detail in
the next lecture next Monday.

01:30:32.290 --> 01:30:34.990
But this is why we went
through all this trouble

01:30:34.990 --> 01:30:37.270
to derive the
paraxial approximation

01:30:37.270 --> 01:30:39.660
and then write it out
in this matrix form,

01:30:39.660 --> 01:30:44.460
so that we can use matrix
properties to do ray tracing.

